name: Riff Raff & Friends ~ 3 Bands all day@Swabbies
description:
Fantastic Rock n Roll Band ...Will have you on your feet for the whole show

Biography
Formed in March 2007, RIFF/RAFF consists of five musicians from the Sacramento area with one goal in mind: High Voltage Rock and Roll! No standing still on stage for these guys… the legacy of AC/DC demands 110% effort and RIFF/RAFF delivers.

RIFF/RAFF’s collective talent allows them to perform songs from the entire AC/DC catalog. Mike Barnes nails the vocal styles of both legendary front-men, Bon Scott and Brian Johnson. The oft-overlooked rhythm section of AC/DC is represented in true RIFF/RAFF style by Michael Spencer (as Cliff Williams), Joel Proto (as Malcolm Young) and Steve Marshall (as Phil Rudd). Together, they form a cohesive unit of sonic thunder that is certain to shake your foundation.

When asked to describe AC/DC in one word, most fans would simply reply, “Angus”. Voted the all-time, #1 rock icon by Kerrang! Magazine in 2007, Angus Young is the embodiment of rock and roll. Hitting the stage in Angus’ patented schoolboy outfit and brandishing his signature Gibson SG, David Chapman channels Angus’ spirit into each and every performance, firing off riffs and solos so close to the original that you’ll wonder if you are actually watching Angus’ twin in action.

RIFF/RAFF prides themselves on an overall production and performance true to the nature and legacy of the legendary Rock and Roll Hall of Fame group, AC/DC.

RIFF/RAFF's blistering performances have garnered praise from the fans of Sacramento's classic rock station, ‘96.9, The Eagle’, and endorsements from legendary classic rock radio host Tom Nakashima. Pat Martin, radio host at 98.5 KRXQ (‘98 Rock’), commented that RIFF/RAFF is a "class act and his favorite tribute band."

Come see why RIFF/RAFF is the premier AC/DC Tribute Band

Cover Charge TBD. Kids free w/ paid responsible adult.

Questions, Message me privately....
Ciao~

Sky

how_to_find_us: Detailed directions will be emailed to each participant who registers at http://www.cityscape-photo.com/workshops/2019/5/11/south-of-bethesda-terrace-central-park-photo-workshop
name: South of Bethesda Terrace: Central Park Photo Workshop
venue_name: Central Park Information Kiosk Columbus Circle
description:
**** NOTE! BEFORE your RSVP to this Workshop, please go to Please go to http://www.cityscape-photo.com/workshops/2019/5/11/south-of-bethesda-terrace-central-park-photo-workshop to register and pay ****

Saturday in the Park! What could be better…except a Photo Workshop with popular photo tour leader and Central Park maven Steve Rosenbach!

On this photo workshop, we’ll explore the visual delights of the southern portion of the “Lower Park,” that is, between Bethesda Terrace (at W 72nd Street) south to Central Park South.

I’ve carefully designed this workshop so as to get the maximum amount of great photo opportunities within about a 3 hour easy walk. I’m limiting the number of people who can attend, so that I can spend time with each of you to help with anything you need in getting really compelling images of the sites that we visit along the way. That can range from basic photo or camera help to assistance with composition and advanced techniques.

During this workshop, we’ll cover most of the south end of the Park, There will be good opportunities for street photography along The Mall, with its many vendors and street performers. As we move further along, we’ll encounter continuously varying, photogenic landscapes, thanks to the brilliance of the Park’s designers over over 150 years ago. You’ll be able to put your own creative stamp on the view of Gapstow Bridge with the Midtown skyline in the background, one of the most iconic scenes in the Park. We’ll cover many of the bridges and arches in this stretch of the Park, each with it’s own unique design and character.

Also, as an added value, you'll be able to send me your photos (or links to them) from this workshop for evaluation and feedback. I'll make comments and suggestions, and in many cases, do some photo editing on your photos to demonstrate how to make a good image even better.

It will be a journey that will delight your sense of color, texture, and proportion as well as refresh your spirit.

EARLY BIRD SPECIAL! Register by April 15, 2019, and take advantage of $10 off the regular price!

BONUS! All participants will receive a gift card worth $25 towards prints and other photo products at Nations Photo Lab https://www.nationsphotolab.com/

**** NOTE! BEFORE your RSVP to this Workshop, please go to Please go to http://www.cityscape-photo.com/workshops/2019/5/11/south-of-bethesda-terrace-central-park-photo-workshop to register and pay ****

how_to_find_us: Nos vemos en el bar tomando un café
name: Larga Exposición Diurna (LED)
description:
Os proponemos un Taller de Fotografía de Larga Exposición Diurna (LED) en la laguna El Campillo, dónde vamos a desarrollar una jornada teórico/práctica de ésta técnica sobre fotografía de paisajismo.

¿Qué haremos?
Impartiremos la teoría y la llevaremos a cabo mientras bordeamos la laguna. Además, visitaremos el Centro de educación ambiental El Campillo, el puente de Arganda y la vía férrea del tren de Arganda.

Hablaremos de los distintos filtros que te ayudarán a resolver este tipo de fotografía y veremos cuando/cómo sacarles el mejor partido.

Al finalizar el Taller tomaremos unas cañas/cafés para descansar y comentar la experiencia, antes de despedirnos 😉

Precio de la actividad, 12€ por persona.

• Contenido teórico
~ Configuración de la cámara para larga exposición
~ Recomendaciones para escoger la mejor configuración: Modo Asistido/Modo Manual
~ Técnicas para la fotografía panorámica (Horizontal/Vertical)
~ Técnicas para el apilamiento de imágenes (HDR)
~ Uso de filtros de densidad neutra y degradados

• Ejercicios prácticos
~ Fotografía panorámica (Horizontal/Vertical)
~ Apilamiento de imágenes en varias exposiciones (HDR)
~ Uso de filtros de densidad neutra y degradados

• Equipo fotográfico recomendado
~ Cámara
~ Trípode
~ Filtros: Polarizador y Densidad Neutra (ND)
~ Tarjetas de memoria y baterías para la cámara

• Lo que hay que llevar
~ Calzado cómodo (deportivas o zapatillas de trekking)
~ Agua, gorra y protector solar

• Información importante
~ Número mínimo/máximo de personas: 5/10
~ Transporte en vehículos privados.
~ Si tenéis preguntas, dudas o necesidad de alguna aclaración, por favor, no dudéis en llamar o escribir, JAIME:[masked]
~ Por favor, para evitar esperas y por respeto al resto de compañeros, si estáis apuntados y finalmente no vais a venir, debéis salir del evento o avisarme con la mayor antelación.
~ En caso de necesidad, cambio meteorológico y siempre por seguridad del grupo, la ruta podría sufrir cambios.

name: Cervantes y Hemingway; conoce dónde vivieron + lugares clave en sus vidas
venue_name: Calle de Atocha, 85 (Delante del portal N 85. Metro más cercano Antón Martín y Atocha)
description:
El sábado descubrirás in situ los diferentes lugares frecuentados por estos dos grandes escritores durante su estancia en Madrid. Verás por ejemplo, la pensión madrileña donde Ernest Hemingway se alojó con su familia entre 1923 y 1926, así como dónde vivió Miguel de Cervantes, en qué taberna escribió la segunda parte del Quijote y en qué calle madrileña falleció.

Precio 6 euros; 5 si se abonan con antelación en la web: www.planbclub.es

Comenzaremos este sábado viendo el lugar donde se encontraban los talleres de la imprenta que a principios de 1605 llevó a cabo la primera edición de El ingenioso Hidalgo Don Quijote de la Mancha.

Desde este punto de partida, nos iremos desplazando para ver el edificio donde vivió y murió Cervantes, así como otros muchos lugares emblemáticos en la vida de estos dos grandes de la literatura.

Entre otros secretos descubriremos a qué restaurante le encantaba acudir a Hemingway para deleitarse con su famoso cochinillo, dónde escribió sus mejores crónicas sobre la guerra civil española. La Calle Huertas, la Gran Vía o Cuchilleros serán algunos de los puntos donde nos detendremos para contemplar puntos importantes en la vida de los protagonistas de esta interesante ruta.

Te esperamos!!

About: The Milky Way Galaxy is one of the most interesting naked eye sights in the night sky. We live under light-polluted skies and to see a glimpse of the Milkyway, we need to travel outside the city. Stay outside in full darkness for a few minutes, then look up. There will be a faint "river" of light crossing the sky. That's the Milky way. Full dark adaptation occurs after 30 minutes of not seeing any source of light, but this is not required for seeing our galaxy.

how_to_find_us: We will meet outside the gate at 7:30 PM for a quick lesson on "Light Painting". The Hollywood Cemetery guard will let us in promptly at 8 PM. The main gate will be re-locked and latecomers will NOT be allowed in.
name: Light Painting with Rob Laurence
description:
Since the Assigned Subject for CCR's June Evaluation is "Night Photography", we thought it would be fun to learn about and practice some "Light Painting". And what better place in Richmond than Hollywood Cemetery?!

Join CCR Member, Rob Laurence for a night-time expedition to Hollywood for a brief lesson on "Light Painting" and a chance to practice those skills (with some expert guidance and mentoring) in this beautiful, historic cemetery.

We will meet outside the gate at 7:30 PM for a quick lesson on "Light Painting". The Hollywood Cemetery guard will let us in promptly at 8 PM. The main gate will be re-locked and latecomers will NOT be allowed in. We must stay together as a group and leave together promptly at 10 PM.

There is a $10 fee for this event so we can make a donation to Hollywood Cemetery. Please bring cash or a check payable to CCR with you. We will also publish a list of equipment you need to bring, so stay tuned for more information as we get closer to the date.

We will reschedule if the weather does not cooperate, so please check back before you leave home if things look iffy.

If you want more in-depth information about light painting, you can also join Rob at our May "Mini-Module" (May 8th, 6:15 PM, right before the Camera Club of Richmond Monthly Meeting).

*** What to Bring ***

We will be shooting long exposures (1-5 minutes perhaps) at low ISO (100 or 200), and augmenting the scene by adding highlights. Given that, you will need:
- A sturdy tripod
- A remote shutter release, preferably an intervelometer or some other method for timing an exposure longer than thirty seconds. A stopwatch will do in a pinch
- Any lens of your choosing. A fast lens in not needed. I'll be bringing my 24-70mm, 16-35mm, and probably a 21mm prime.
- A red-light flashlight. As our eyes adjust to the low light, you will still need something to see your camera controls (or the ground as you walk.) The red light will allow you and everyone else to keep our night vision.
- Another flashlight (or more)for light painting. Consider how it will affect white balance. LED is good, incandescent can be good, fluorescent is not so good imho.
- If you like, a snoot (in its most simple form, an empty toilet paper or paper towel roll) to tape to your flashlight for 'precision' light painting
- Extra Batteries!!!!
- Of course, creature comforts - water, appropriate clothing, even a chair if you don't mind carrying it.

name: Henley, Stonor, Turville & Thames - Extra Long Hilly Country Hike
description:
Walk length 20miles/32km approx. Circular.

A spectacular and long circular hike from Henley to Stonor and Turville with far reaching views across open countryside and the Thames.

This hike has a great deal of features..

Stonor Park includes an historic country house and private deer park situated about four miles (6.4 km) north of Henley-on-Thames.

At Turville there will be an opportunity to climb to the top of windmill hill for great views of the surrounding countryside close to the Cobstone windmill. The Cobstone windmill was built around 1816 and featured in the film "Chitty Chitty Bang Bang."

The final section of the walk follows the Thames path from Mill End back to Henley.

PLEASE BE AWARE THIS IS A VERY LONG HILLY HIKE SO PLEASE ONLY RSVP IF YOU ARE COMFORTABLE WITH THIS AND CAN KEEP A REASONABLE PACE. BE AWARE IF THE WEATHER IS BAD THE HIKE MAY BE SHORTENED.

Cost

£6 cash guided hike/meetup

Train £17.70 return but may be reduced by a third with a network railcard or groupsave discount.

Lunch and Finish

Please bring a packed lunch and water for the walk. The walk should finish before 6.00pm and includes a pack lunch stop and pub stop at the end, however the time may be earlier or later than this depending on the weather and pace (this is a complete day hike, you are advised not to arrange anything for the evening).

We will probably use the Barn at Turville Heath for our pack lunch stop which will be about halfway. The Barn is a farm shop and no-car cafe.
We will use the Catherine Wheel pub at Henley after the walk which is close to the station (10min walk) does food and is very reasonably priced.

Meeting points please read..

Meet outside Henley train station for the walk to start at 10.20am (after the train from London arrives).

By train from London: The London Paddington train at 9.15am gets to Henley-on-Thames for 10.20am with a short change at Twyford (times correct at time of publishing/please check before travel). I would encourage you to seek out other members who can go as part of a group save on the train and meet at 8.30am to give you time to get tickets.

I would suggest you meet outside the WHSmith shop at Paddington to give you time to get a group save and buy tickets as you may have to queue (see photo below). See National Rail Enquiries (http://www.nationalrail.co.uk/)

Car: The station car park at Henley charges but there are a number of off road streets that should be free on a Sunday, please leave enough time to park and check for restrictions.

Please make a note of the organizers numbers - Colin[masked].

RSVP: If you can't make this walk please change your RSVP before the start of the walk. Please see our RSVP policy (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/RSVP_for_Walks/).

The organizer will not be taking the train but will meet you at Henley.

Dog Policy: As a group we allow and enjoy dogs on our walks however we do ask dog owners to read our dog policy (http://www.meetup.com/London-Explorers/pages/9823882/Dog_Policy/)

Walking Safety

Walking is a great way to keep fit and generally very safe; however it does contain an element of risk. Before going on any of these walks you need to be reasonably fit and be prepared to be responsible for your own safety. You should wear appropriate clothing such as proper walking shoes, warm and wet weather clothing and carry sufficient food and water. Please see our Terms and Conditions (http://www.meetup.com/London-Explorers/pages/3170152/Terms_and_Conditions/)

COULD EVERYONE PLEASE AVOID COMMENTS BELOW THAT ARE NOT SPECIFIC TO THE EVENT AS THIS GENERATES SPAM, JUST CHANGE YOUR RSVP IF YOU CAN'T GO. YOU CAN MESSAGE ME. MANY THANKS.

name: The Nesting Ecology of Birds: A Field Experience-Part One
description:
Every couple weeks we will go experience what can be gleaned from watching nesting birds in their territories, visiting different locations and learning how they cope in a world of competition and danger. We will visit various locations chosen for their diversity of birds. We will go from woodlands to grasslands, to wetlands like lakes, ponds, bogs, etc.
This should be full of incredible sights and experiences for all who can come. Both learning in the outdoor "classroom" and getting close enough to observe birds in all their beauty and wonder if what we are doing in these classes. I truly hope you can make it to some of them.
We may offer an optional lunch to share what we saw and hear some good bird stories. I require no fees for my time, but ask that you consider helping me pay fees to do this for members.
I am also putting up bird houses for our smaller birds who often find it difficult to find safe places to raise young because the nest location is not a safe one from invaders, who are many.

how_to_find_us: You will receive an email with directions
name: Bluebirds and Swallow Photography Workshop
description:
Bluebirds and Swallows are beautiful and fascinating birds that compete for lodging around Calgary. They compete with each other and they compete across species.

This outing, hosted by Don Orchard, will take you to a location south of the city where you will learn techniques to capture images of these fast and unpredictable birds.

The class will run from 9 am until 2 pm and everyone who registers for the session will receive a 'Bird Photography' guide in advance of the outing. The guide will tell you how to set up your camera for success and you will receive hands-on support in the field.

All participants should bring a 200mm or longer lens. Lenses can be rented at Vistek or the Camera Store if you want a lens that is longer than what you have now.

We will set-up car-pooling for the outing. Those details plus maps and more will be provided in the welcome note that is sent to everyone taking part.

To receive your welcome note please be sure to email Don at [masked] as soon as you have signed-up. And please let him know if you can be a driver for car-pooling purposes.

Credit card and Paypal payments accepted.

Bluebird and Swallow images below captured courtesy of Don.

how_to_find_us: We are in the room to your left once you reach the hostess stand. Plenty of FREE parking in their lot of Jeffords St. Doors open at 8:30 AM
name: Advanced Composition — Part 4 of 4
description:
Composition is perhaps the hardest part of photography. This course will explain composition in a new way and teach many of the advanced techniques that the masters have developed and used for centuries.

The classes are presented in the form of a Keynote (Powerpoint) and have dozens of visual examples to reinforce the topics being presented. At the end of the class the students will be given an optional assignment. Assignments will be shared online in a safe and private group just for the students in this FCCP class. This will allow extra interaction with instructors and fellow students.

The class is being held 4 Sunday mornings at O'keefe's Family Restaurant in Clearwater. Topics covered will include,

* Learning to Pre-visualize

* Focal Points

* Introduction to Formats

* The Use of Space and Negative Space

* The Power and Use of Shape

* The Power and Use of Color

* The Power and Use of Rhythm

* Perspective and Angle of View

* and much, much more . . .

The classes are being recorded and will be made available to those students that attend the classes. Following the class is an optional Q&A lunch. This will allow students extra time to ask questions and interact with the instructor.

how_to_find_us: The studio is in back of the brick house at 329 East 3rd Street. Please do not disturb the folks there. Walk down the driveway on the west side (mountain) of the brick house to get to the studio, the building is called 3rd Street Studios.
name: Intro to Lightroom Classic CC - part of PPA Super 1 Day events nationwide
description:
Hosted by PPA (Professional Photographers of America)

$99 before May 1st, $120 after

Must sign up on PPA.com site listed below.

https://www.ppa.com/events/intro-to-adobe-lightroom-classic-cc-5-12-2019?fbclid=IwAR1f1fboUpxr8ijuUhtaJAdz9eXodNZ1E5MlSb7qCBmJUzV-XTBiA6vqx0w#.XIhrJLHNO74.facebook

Lightroom can be intimidating and confusing. This class will lead the student, with hands on activities, to import images, basic manipulation and exporting the final result. We will be using the current version of Lightroom Classic CC which needs to be LOADED and able to RUN on your computer.

Example workflows
- Basics of how Lightroom handles images.
- The different panels within Lightroom
- Importing images
- Image manipulation, color correction, cropping.
... everything to produce a final image.
- Image exporting
- Backing up the Lightroom files
- Practice, practice, practice....

name: American Cancer Society's Courageous Kids Day - VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITY
group_name: Professional Photographers of Santa Clara Valley
description:
ACS's Courageous Kids Day is celebrating its 30th year this Mother's Day. This day was started as a "day off from cancer" for children with cancer and their families. Great America has hosted this wonderful event every year, providing the picnic grove, free tickets, lunch, staff, and so much more to the families of[masked] children each year. The event is mostly staffed by about 200 volunteers, many of whom have been volunteering for many many years. There are lots of fun activities happening for the kids and their families, including celebrities, sand castle building, games, music, arts & crafts, face painting, quilt production, food, fun, and.... and this is where we come in.... FAMILY PORTRAITS!

We need your help. We need about 20 photographers to volunteer for this incredible event. Most will be in teams doing professional family portraits, and a few will be doing candid photographs around the event venue. Whether you're a seasoned professional or a beginner, this is a very rewarding event. If you're new to the profession please feel free to volunteer. We'll be grouping less experienced photographers with more experienced, so everyone will be able to participate and learn.

Each attending family will be entitled to a free professional family portrait. In many cases, this is the only portrait this family has, or may ever have. It means so much to the families, and you'll feel their love and appreciation all day.

In order to participate, you'll need to RSVP. I'll get back to you with questions and to confirm your participation. Do NOT show up unless you've been confirmed, as you will not be admitted.

VERY IMPORTANT: Please only volunteer if you are really committed to being there. This is a big event and we need everyone there who says they'll be there. Thank you.

If you have questions, please feel free to email me by clicking on the ORGANZER link on the left side of this page.

how_to_find_us: We will gather infront of the Chelsea Hotel at 33 Gerrad St West
name: Explore Victorian Toronto – Walking Tour
description:
Join us for a tour in Downtown Toronto! We will visit Allan Gardens, Toronto Necropolis, and Riverdale Farm. This is a great way of visiting some of Toronto’s iconic places. We will show you around as a local.

We will meet in front of the Chelsea Hotel, and we will start our tour by walking on Gerrard St. We will see some interesting places along the way, but our first stop is going to be at Allan Gardens. Enjoy a collection of flora from around the world housed in a cast-iron and glass building dating to 1910.

Our next stop will be the Toronto Necropolis, one of the city’s oldest and most historic cemeteries featuring Gothic architecture and the tombs of many important Torontonians. After our visit we will take a break and we will go to our next stop.

We will walk to Riverdale Farm (our last stop), were you can get a first-hand experience of farm life in downtown Toronto. We will see a variety of animals, vegetable and herbs gardens. After the tour is over feel free to stay and chat with other members of the meetup!

THIS TOUR INCLUDES:
• Allan Gardens
• Cabbage Town
• Toronto Necropolis
• Riverdale Farm

WHEN AND WHERE TO MEET?
10:00 am – Chelsea Hotel (Meeting in front of the lobby at 33 Gerrard St W)

PAYMENT:
Free --> NOTE: Our tours guides are independent, freelancers or volunteers and they do the tour for free. However, if you enjoy the experience, tips are welcome. There is no obligation, but by tipping the tour guide you will help us to pay the meetup fees and keep the tours running.

WHAT TO BRING?
Comfortable clothes, water, and camera

CONTACT INFO:
- Cell phone[masked]
- or Meetup message

name: Monthly Photo Walk - Muller Farmers Market
description:
MONTHLY PHOTOWALK

This is a great way for the community of photographers to get together. We will walk a predetermined path. You're free to wonder! Everyone can discover new places to shoot, discus the way your neighbor got that shot and you can play with your camera in new ways you may not have thought of before!

• Each month we will pick a different location to walk. As the time of sunrise changes we will adjust the meeting time to be about 15 minute prior to sunrise and starting to walk PROMPTLY at 15 minutes later.

• The walk will be about 1 hour.

• Walks will be about 1 mile round trip. I think =-P. I'll link a google map of the intended path.

• Walks will generally be in a paved or well pathed area.

• This is Texas y'all... bring water, dress appropriately for the weather and know your own abilities and limitations.

I'm going to work on plans for posting and discussing your favorite images after the walk.... suggestions as to how or where and when are welcome. For now, the experience will be the walk with fellow photographers. You CAN however, post your images on this specific meetup event immediately if you would like!

That's it... hope to see you there!

Brandon Burkhardt

= = = Notes = = =

What is a Photowalk? Photowalk according to Wikipedia: "Photowalking (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Photowalking)is a communal activity of camera enthusiasts who gather in a group to walk around with a camera (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Camera) for the main purpose of taking pictures of things that interests each photographer. Although the term implies the single activity of taking pictures while walking, the more modern use of the term specifically relates to a communal activity of camera enthusiasts."

WHY 7:00AM? I can guarantee you just about every great photo ever taken was taken at an uncomfortable time and in a place most people never go. That is when and where the rare and special moments are! Oh yeah... and golden hour. Golden hour is the time of day when the sun is nearest the horizon and the natural light is at it's absolute best. Sunrise and Sunset!

how_to_find_us: Just inside the park gate on the blacktop
name: The Mysterious Wrecked Volvo (Car Wreck) in Aliso Woods Wilderness Park
description:
***This hike is to the Volvo at the bottom of Car Wreck Trail, very near by Dripping Cave. There was a fire in June that has Dripping Cave CLOSED***

*** The last few times we've seen members of the local Bobcat family ***

The hike is about 8 miles round trip. There are a few narrow and winding trails, but nothing too steep. Part of the route follows Aliso Creek under the oak trees, then it opens up and we'll pass some of the remnants of the local ranching days. Dripping Cave, AKA Robbers Cave, was used by stagecoach robbers when Wells Fargo ran through here 'a little while back'... We'll pass the closed Dripping Cave trail head and go another 15-20 minutes up to the bottom of Car Wreck trail. Turn the corner past the Volvo when you get there and take a look up the side of the hill... It does that for a lonnnnng time..... Then it's back out and slow and steadily back up to the park where we started... Plan for about three hours total.

Local Weather Link (http://forecast.weather.gov/MapClick.php?lat=33.5519&lon=-117.7203#.WZJJg-mQzIU)

PDF Park Map (http://www.ocparks.com/civicax/filebank/blobdload.aspx?BlobID=57856)

Park Web Site (http://www.ocparks.com/parks/aliso)

Aliso and Wood Canyons Wilderness Park:

Approximately 4,500 acres of wilderness and natural open space land. Originally, part of the Juaneno or Acajchemem tribal land, it later was owned by Don Juan Avila, Louis Moulton, The Mission Viejo Company and now is under the jurisdiction of OC Parks. Within the park lands are mature oaks, sycamores, and elderberry trees, two year round streams and over 30 miles of official trails. Many rare and endangered plants and animals make this park their home. This park is designated as a wildlife sanctuary.

PARKING IS AN ISSUE HERE... ***PLEASE READ THIS*** Do not park on the down hill portion of Canyon Vistas street. You will get a $40 ticket. Park going uphill on Canyon Vistas, or use the side streets Costal Oak or Rockrose... You can also park on Silkwood, which is to the left at the bottom of Canyon Vistas. *** The right side ("Madia ln") is a private community and you need a permit to park on that side.*** ***Again, please note that the right side of Canyon Vistas at the bottom of the hill is a long no parking zone that only has a few signs, the curb is not painted red.*** I park on the side streets up the hill above the park... and it's a little flatter...

There are no restrooms on the trail. There is a portable restroom in the park, and dogs are not permitted...

I think that's it... Any questions, please ask... Thanks...

name: Chorleywood & the Chess Valley
description:
Walk length 10 miles/16 km approx. Circular.

The Chess Valley has some of the most attractive countryside in the Chilterns Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty.

Walk Description

The walk starts from Chorleywood Station and then crosses Chorleywood Common, an attractive 76 hectares of grassland and woodland. The mix of grassland, ponds and woodland provides excellent conditions for a wide range of flora and fauna. We then take a route following a loop along the Chess Valley with the mid-point at the village of Latimer. This is a landscape rich in wildlife, with a long and fascinating history. We will pass the site of a Roman farm-villa at Latimer, and the 13th century Chenies Manor visited by Elizabeth I. There will be a short stop at the watercress beds at Sarratt, the only commercial watercress farm left in the Chilterns.

History and Trivia

A village settlement has been at Chorleywood since Roman times. During the 17th century after the Turnpike act it was able to use its favourable location as a major point on the road between Hatfield and Reading to charge for its road use. Extensions of the Metropolitan Railway to Chorleywood in the 19th Century brought it into the rapidly developing commuter belt of London and further population growth. In the 1960's researchers at Chorleywood improved on established bread making processes (Chorleywood Bread Process), this is now used in 80% of the current UK bread production. The village of Latimer is particularly attractive with a number of 17th and 18th century cottages surrounding a small village green with a green pump.

Lunch and Finish

Please bring a packed lunch and water for the walk. The walk will finish at about 17.00pm and include a 30 min lunch stop, however the time may be earlier or later than this depending on the weather and pace (we have a relaxed pace which includes sightseeing and photography).

Meeting and Transport

Meet at the entrance to Chorleywood Railway Station from 11.00am for the walk to start at 11.15am.

Car: There is free parking close to the station such as Lower Rd, and the common car park, the station charges on a Sunday. Please check for parking restrictions.

Train from London : The 10.42am train from London Marylebone gets to Chorleywood for 11.09am.

I would suggest meeting outside the WHSmith shop at London Marylebone from 10.00am to give you time to meet others for any group save tickets (see picture below).

Please note the organizer will not be taking the train from London Marylebone but will meet you at Chorleywood.

See Chiltern Railways (http://www.chilternrailways.co.uk/).

Chorleywood is also served by the Metropolitan Underground line.

See Transport for London (http://www.tfl.gov.uk/)

I would encourage you to seek other members who can take advantage of a group save on the train.

Please make a note of the organizers numbers - Leon[masked]

RSVP: The organizers monitor non-attendance; please update your RSVP beforehand. Please see our RSVP policy (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/RSVP_for_Walks/)

Weather: See also BBC Weather (http://www.bbc.co.uk/weather/)
Please see our weather policy (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/Weather/)

Dog Policy: As a group we allow and enjoy dogs on our walks however we do ask dog owners to read our dog policy (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/Dog_Policy/)

Walking Safety

Walking is a great way to keep fit and generally very safe; however it does contain an element of risk. Before going on any of these walks you need to be reasonably fit and be prepared to be responsible for your own safety. You must wear appropriate clothing such as proper walking boots, warm and wet weather clothing and carry sufficient food and water. Please see our Terms and Conditions (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/Terms_and_Conditions/)

group_name: Chiltern Explorers - Hikes, Walking Weekends, Socials
description:

A spectacular and long circular hike from Henley to Stonor and Turville with far reaching views across open countryside and the Thames.

This hike has a great deal of features..

Stonor Park includes an historic country house and private deer park situated about four miles (6.4 km) north of Henley-on-Thames.

At Turville there will be an opportunity to climb to the top of windmill hill for great views of the surrounding countryside close to the Cobstone windmill. The Cobstone windmill was built around 1816 and featured in the film "Chitty Chitty Bang Bang."

The final section of the walk follows the Thames path from Mill End back to Henley.

PLEASE BE AWARE THIS IS A VERY LONG HILLY HIKE SO PLEASE ONLY RSVP IF YOU ARE COMFORTABLE WITH THIS AND CAN KEEP A REASONABLE PACE. BE AWARE IF THE WEATHER IS BAD THE HIKE MAY BE SHORTENED.

The walk should finish before 6.00pm and includes a pack lunch stop and pub stop at the end, however the time may be earlier or later than this depending on the weather and pace (this is a complete day hike, you are advised not to arrange anything for the evening).

We will probably use the Barn at Turville Heath for our pack lunch stop which will be about halfway. The Barn is a farm shop and no-car cafe.
We will use the Catherine Wheel pub at Henley after the walk which is close to the station (10min walk) does food and is very reasonably priced.

You should wear appropriate clothing such as proper walking boots, warm and wet weather clothing and carry sufficient food and water. name: Photo Walk: London's Westend and Chinatown
description:
Join us for a photowalk taking in the Westend and Chinatown. Photowalks are a great way for you to practice your camera skills and learn new ways to compose and shoot and things. They are also great for meeting people that love the same thing as you do!

There will be plenty of opportunity to shoot people, places and architecture so definitely something for everyone.

This workshop is aimed at people with:
• all abilities
• any camera
• any lens
• An open mind and fun
• No tripod needed

This is not a teaching session but support will be given with camera settings if you need it.

Come along, meet some new people and have a great day out with us!

TRAVEL
As usual check the TFL website for any issues that may delay your journey. If you're running late or can't see us ring Alex on[masked]

Check out our full calendar of events:
https://www.meetup.com/londonphotographic/events/calendar

name: Bikes, Camera, Action! Mark II
venue_address_1: 2 Marina Blvd, Building B of Fort Mason Center
description:
Let's meet Sunday May, 12 (Mother's Day) at Goody Cafe at Fort Mason, bike through Chrissy Field then up to the Presidio Picnic on Montgomery Street.

There are bike rentals in front of Fort Mason for those who don't own a bike. It's best to park in front of the yacht harbor adjacent to Fort Mason or Uber/Lyft to it. Don't forget to bring a helmet, lock and chain, lots of water and an easy to carry pack for your gear.

Because we are biking, remember to carry light. Great way to practice on one camera and one lens. Expect to walk bikes at certain times as we will be climbing hills. We'll enjoy stopping in the many stops to take pictures but ultimately we'll have a great time eating at the food booths and food trucks at the Picnic at the Presidio for lunch (Sundays 11a-4p). Here is what you can expect from the Presidio Picnic: https://www.presidio.gov/events/presidio-picnic

Here's a review about the Presidio Picnic by two budding foodies: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3PEC0YuD06g&t=1s

name: VISITAMOS LA CASA DE SOROLLA Y ENTRAMOS A UN PALACIO BURGUÉS DEL S XIX
description:
Comenzaremos esta apasionante RUTA EN INTERIORES SIN FRÍO NI LLUVIA VISITANDO LA QUE FUE LA CASA DEL PINTOR SOROLLA EN CHAMBERÍ Y SU ESPECTACULAR JARDÍN inspirado en el Jardín de Troya del Alcázar de Sevilla, y el Generalife de Granada. Esta vivienda hoy en día se ha convertido en el museo de Sorolla. Veremos todas las colecciones, las cuales se distribuyen por todas las zonas visitables de la casa, que ha conservado casi intacta la decoración que tuvo en vida de Joaquín Sorolla. La colección de pintura convive, por tanto, con el mobiliario y los objetos originales de la vivienda. SE TRATA DE UNA DE LAS CASAS DEL ARTISTA MEJOR CONSERVADAS EN EUROPA.

Precio: 7 euros; 5 si se abonan con antelación en la web www.planbclub.es

¿Te has preguntado alguna vez CÓMO VIVÍA EN ESPAÑA LA ALTA BURGUESÍA entre 1833 y 1868?

Descúbrelo este domingo VISITANDO UN AUTÉNTICO PALACIO BURGUÉS del S XIX, donde verás una recreación de la vida cotidiana y costumbres de quienes fueron sus propietarios a través de pinturas, dibujos, esculturas, mobiliario, fotografías....ASÍ COMO NUMEROSOS SECRETOS DE ESTA CLASE SOCIAL EN ESA ÉPOCA.

En este viaje único por el pasado también NOS DETENDREMOS EN en uno de los restaurantes de la zona con verdadera solera de Madrid, INAUGURADO EN 1908 Y QUE HA FORMADO PARTE DEL ESCENARIO DE UNA DE LAS PELÍCULAS DE ALMODOVAR.

Merece la pena emplear esta mañana de domingo en este apasionante y único viaje al pasado ¿verdad?

how_to_find_us: Meet at 11.00 for a prompt start at 11.15. Parking on the Grindleford station approach road. Nearest postcode S32 2HY
name: Level 2/3⛅10mile Walk⛅Grindleford Eyam Stoney Middleton Calver Froggatt⛅
group_name: Get Fit Derbyshire 🐣 Spring Into Action! 🐣
description:
This 10 mile scenic walk starts at Grindleford Station and goes through quaint Historical Villages.

First, we make our way to the beautiful Historic Village of Eyam which became famous after the black death of[masked] and is known as the plague Village.

Onto the quaint and interesting Village of Stoney Middleton, the deep and dramatic limestone gorge cuts through the Village. Houses appear to cling to rocky ledges providing a picture postcard image of this unusual dale.

We leave Stoney Middleton and follow paths and fields down into the steep sided Coombs Dale limestone valley. It's an area of scientific interest and importance for its conservation.

Descending to the stone built Village of Calver with lovely old cottages and an 18th Century bridge over the River Derwent.

The route now follows the Derwent back to Grindleford. Going through the picturesque Village of Froggatt set below a gritstone edge and alongside the scenic wooded banks of the Derwent. Quaint little cottages with pretty gardens nestle below the rugged craggs of Froggatt edge. Leaving the Village we go through Froggatt wood and onto the Grindleford road.

This walk is suitable for anyone with a good level of fitness, as always we'll have regular catching up points along the way.

Good walking boots and a waterproof just in case..

Make sure you bring enough food and water to keep you going. We'll have a picnic lunch stop along the way.

There's no toilet stop at the start of the walk unless you buy something from the Station Cafe. They are strict about customer usage only.. But we'll have a toilet stop once we get to Eyam about an hour into the walk.

Dogs are always welcome 😊🐾🐾🐾

Pub stop at the end of the walk in Grindleford.

Car sharing is easier and cheaper for everyone so please post a message if you're willing to share a lift.

name: Chorleywood and the Chess Valley
group_name: Chiltern Explorers - Hikes, Walking Weekends, Socials
description:
Walk length 10 miles/16 km approx. Circular.

The Chess Valley has some of the most attractive countryside in the Chilterns Area of Outstanding Natural Beauty.

Walk Description

The walk starts from Chorleywood Station and then crosses Chorleywood Common, an attractive 76 hectares of grassland and woodland. The mix of grassland, ponds and woodland provides excellent conditions for a wide range of flora and fauna. We then take a route following a loop along the Chess Valley with the mid-point at the village of Latimer. This is a landscape rich in wildlife, with a long and fascinating history. We will pass the site of a Roman farm-villa at Latimer, and the 13th century Chenies Manor visited by Elizabeth I. There will be a short stop at the watercress beds at Sarratt, the only commercial watercress farm left in the Chilterns.

History and Trivia

A village settlement has been at Chorleywood since Roman times. During the 17th century after the Turnpike act it was able to use its favourable location as a major point on the road between Hatfield and Reading to charge for its road use. Extensions of the Metropolitan Railway to Chorleywood in the 19th Century brought it into the rapidly developing commuter belt of London and further population growth. In the 1960's researchers at Chorleywood improved on established bread making processes (Chorleywood Bread Process), this is now used in 80% of the current UK bread production. The village of Latimer is particularly attractive with a number of 17th and 18th century cottages surrounding a small village green with a green pump.

Lunch and Finish

Please bring a packed lunch and water for the walk. The walk will finish at about 17.00pm and include a 30 min lunch stop, however the time may be earlier or later than this depending on the weather and pace (we have a relaxed pace which includes sightseeing and photography).

Meeting and Transport

Meet at the entrance to Chorleywood Railway Station from 11.00am for the walk to start at 11.15am.

Car: There is free parking close to the station such as Lower Rd, and the common car park, the station charges on a Sunday. Please check for parking restrictions.

Train from London : The 10.42am train from London Marylebone gets to Chorleywood for 11.09am.

I would suggest meeting outside the WHSmith shop at London Marylebone from 10.00am to give you time to meet others for any group save tickets (see picture below).

Please note the organizer will not be taking the train from London Marylebone but will meet you at Chorleywood.

See Chiltern Railways (http://www.chilternrailways.co.uk/).

Chorleywood is also served by the Metropolitan Underground line.

See Transport for London (http://www.tfl.gov.uk/)

I would encourage you to seek other members who can take advantage of a group save on the train.

Please make a note of the organizers numbers - Leon[masked]

RSVP: The organizers monitor non-attendance; please update your RSVP beforehand. Please see our RSVP policy (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/RSVP_for_Walks/)

Weather: See also BBC Weather (http://www.bbc.co.uk/weather/)
Please see our weather policy (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/Weather/)

Dog Policy: As a group we allow and enjoy dogs on our walks however we do ask dog owners to read our dog policy (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/Dog_Policy/)

Walking Safety

Walking is a great way to keep fit and generally very safe; however it does contain an element of risk. Before going on any of these walks you need to be reasonably fit and be prepared to be responsible for your own safety. You must wear appropriate clothing such as proper walking boots, warm and wet weather clothing and carry sufficient food and water. Please see our Terms and Conditions (http://www.meetup.com/Chiltern-Explorers/pages/Terms_and_Conditions/)

how_to_find_us: Meet by entrance to Napier University car park on Glenlockhart Rd. There is a #36 bus stop near by. Please arrive a few mins early if possible (the 36 arrives at 11am from both directions)
name: Mindfulness & nature connection #3
description:
The third workshop in a series (2nd Sunday of the month), each month we connect with a different place in Edinburgh. In this session we will explore how nature deals with stress and how we can apply these insights in our own lives.

There is now a considerable body of evidence showing that connecting with nature and practising mindfulness is beneficial to health and wellbeing. In these sessions you will learn how to heighten your sensory awareness, become more finely attuned to your inner self and deepen your sense of interconnection with the natural world.

WHAT TO BRING
As an outdoor event on uneven or rough ground, please wear sturdy footwear and bring warm & waterproof clothing - there's no such thing as bad weather just inappropriate clothing :-) You may also want to bring a small mat to sit on, and a drink.

£1+ donation as usual to meetup costs.

NB. These sessions are also open to others so numbers are limited for this meetup group. The total group size will be no more than 12.

REDUCE THE ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT OF THIS EVENT - please walk, cycle or use public transport. If that's not possible then please offer car share by posting message below.

About me
I have been practising and teaching mindfulness & nature connection for many years, and have trained in mindfulness teaching. I'm a certified and accredited coach with professional membership of Association for Coaching and work to its code of ethics and to the UK Network for Mindfulness-Based Teachers good practice guidelines. I'm also a qualified Mountain Leader.

Other info
You are responsible for your own safety and wellbeing. All activities are voluntary and you are invited to take part as much or as little as you wish. Any information provided by me is given in good faith but without responsibility on my part. If you have a physical or mental health medical condition that might affect your, or other people’s safety or enjoyment, you should take appropriate medical advice and you must inform me of your condition in advance - send me a private message and we can have a chat by tel if necessary.

how_to_find_us: We will all meet at 11:30 AM at the adventure center registration desk. I will post my mobile number in the comments for those who RSVP.
name: Not So Urban Athletics: Aerial Antics at the Skytop Treetop Adventure Course
group_name: I wanted to do that...Just not alone!!
description:
Is your personal anthem that century old tune, The Daring Young Man on the Flying Trapeze? If you have the faintest idea to what I'm referring then this might be the meetup for you. We're going to spend the day at the Skytop Lodge Treetop Adventure Course.

If you don't know, now you know!

The Skytop Lodge Treetop Adventure Course is an aerial, tree-to-tree adventure park consisting of elevated platforms connected by various configurations of cable, wood, rope and zip lines to form bridges. Have no worries, it's a safe adventure--well, as safe as dangling from ropes 30 feet above ground can be. After you're fitted with a safety harness, we'll be led through a park usage demonstration, given safety gloves, and then guided through four courses of increasing difficulty where we'll be challenged to cross bridges, climb ladders, obstacles, and zoom down sixteen zip lines.

What does it cost and how to pay?

Admission is $60.00 per person for a 4 hour session. Advance registration is REQUIRED! Our group size is limited so DON'T DELAY in registering!

To register, click the link below:

https://www.skytop.com/play/adventure/treetop-adventure-course/

- Click on "Book Now"
- Click "Treetop Adventure Course" (4 hour session)
- Choose "May 12" from the calendar
- Choose the "12:00 PM" session from the drop down
- Enter your information as needed to complete the rest of your registration

Important stuff!

• No experience is necessary but you must be able to reach up to a height of 5'11" while standing flat footed, weigh a maximum of 275 lbs, have a waist size of less than 42" inches, and have a thigh size less than 26" inches

• Admission is for four hours of park time

• Dress for the weather and activity! Clothing should be well-fitted and there should be nothing hanging loose that may get tangled in cables and rope. Long hair and jewelry should be secured. Sneakers or hiking shoes are mandatory

• We go rain or shine, unless there is thunder and lightning

• I will post my mobile phone number in the comments before the event. Don't leave home without it

How do I get there? Drive or carpool!

One Skytop Lodge Road
Skytop, PA 18357

The Skytop Adventure Center is about 1.5 hours east of NYC in the Poconos area of Pennsylvania, there is no public transportation. If you have a car and can offer a carpool, please post that. If you need a ride, make a post in the comments asking for one and the general location you are around town.

name: Kundalini Yoga/Meditation Introduction (Donation Basis)
group_name: I am Happy Project - Zurich, Switzerland
description:
Dear All,
This session is mainly for the people who want to learn kundalini yoga/meditation in a traditional way. Traditionally the master will transfer his kundalini energy to the student to open his chakra (energy center) and third eye. Immediately the student can feel his/her Kundalini Energy is rising from their base of the spine and feeling the energy vibration in the third eye (the space between the eyebrows). This session is helpful for the beginners who want to learn proper meditation also.

What is included in this session?

- Simple stretching practices for Hip and Spine (not complicated, even beginners can do)
- Kundalini Breathing Techniques
- Sound Energy (Mantra) Meditation
- Energy Healing Techniques
- Formal Kundalini Activation (optional and only for interested people)
- Kundalini Meditation
- Yoga Nidra (Relaxation)

Some of the benefits of Kundalini Energy Activation are:

- Keeps the body free from diseases
- Mind will be at its peaceful state, so the meditation is easy to do
- Breathing pattern will be harmonized
- Stress relieve and peace
- Clear & sharp intellect
- More intuition
- Inner happiness
- Clairvoyance and Clairvision
- SELF realization (which will lead to the blissful state - our true state)
- etc.

About the Teacher who conducts this session:

The kundalini wisdom teacher is from India and currently working as a Computer Engineer. He is learning kundalini yoga for the past 14 years under the training of Self Realized Indian Master "Maha MahaRishi Paranjothiyar". He is teaching yoga for the past 10 years as part of "Maha Shakthi Meditation Services, Europe". He teaches Yoga/Meditation/Pranic Healing/Stress Relief courses in various places of Germany and Switzerland. He is the authorized kundalini yoga wisdom teacher to activate the Kundalini Energy in a traditional way (Shaktipat).

All these events are conducted for non-profit purpose. Donations are collected on behalf of a Swiss non-profit organization (Verein) "Maha Shakthi Yogam - Switzerland"

Eligibility:
Anyone can attend the workshop even if they don't have previous yoga experiences.

Dress:
Wear a comfortable dress if possible yoga dress. We provide the yoga mat.

The Locations is :
Room 2 in Selbst Hilfe Center, Zürich.

Please RSVP only you are really interested and coming ! Limited Seats !
RSVP in meetup does not guarantee the course admission.
Send us a private message in Meetup for registration.
Admission is strictly only for people who have registered with us.

About Kundalini Shaktipat:
In every human being there is a source of natural energy that the yogis call the kundalini. In order to evolve in the yogic path, no matter what our path, the kundalini must be active.
For most of us, the kundalini lies dormant at the bottom of the spine in the base chakra known as the Muladhar. When it awakens, it ascends through the chakras until it reaches the highest chakra, the Sahasrar. When that occurs, we merge with our True Self and attain SELF realization (our true nature).

Shaktipat is the transfer of spiritual energy from the teacher to the student in order to awaken the kundalini. This process is compared to lighting one candle with another that is already lit and glowing. When the teacher is connected with the fully realized master and the energy is completely within his or her control, shaktipat initiation ensures that the student’s energy will remain active and stable. "Electricity is present everywhere, but there can be light only when the switch is turned on. Similarly the true master manifests the consciousness in the disciple through shaktipat.”

Introduction Video to explain Kundalini Meditation:

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0Vt6zZgf1Ds&feature=youtu.be

HAPPINESS is our TRUE Nature, which comes from within not from outside !

how_to_find_us: Meet us at 1:00pm midway on the Ushigome-bashi bridge located midway between the West exit of JR Iidabashi station & the B2a exit from the nearby Metro station. Exact Meeting place on Google map: => https://goo.gl/maps/nzR8eQA65HdkPzNC6
name: FREE Kagurazaka O-Edo Music & Culture festival & Historical town walking tour!
description:
Hello everyone!

By request of Tokyo City, we're presenting a free meetup for the Japanese traditional cultural event, “Kagurazaka Street Stage O-edo Tour 2019” on May 12th!

(Or: 神楽坂まち舞台大江戸めぐり!)

This project & event aim to present a variety of traditional performing arts from Japan to people of all ages, in an enjoyable, easy-to-understand way.

It also showcases the charms of Kagurazaka, a deeply traditional and cultural town with the unique charm and mixed atmosphere of old and modern Tokyo, plus a genuine flavor of sophisticated Paris!

----------------------
Event Overview
----------------------

Having the special “RAKUZA” stage at Bishamonten Temple at the center, many events will be held throughout Kagurazaka, including street performances, dances and a Stamp Rally where participants may enjoy walking while exploring this fascinating district.

We will enjoy great Japanese traditional music during the event!

Here, a great blog suggests what we may expect on May 12th:

http://www.thechroniclesofmariane.com/2018/04/Kagurazaka-Oedo-Tokyo-Festival.html

@}:^)

Let's stroll together & enjoy the sense of Japanese culture in Kagurazaka, in harmony with tradition, creativity and humanity!

----------------------
Event Details
----------------------

【Date & Time】May 12th (Sun) 1:00pm - about 4:00 pm.

【Rough schedule】1:00pm: Meeting the group members

1:00-2:00pm: Walking to the center of Kagurazaka
(Bishamonten temple) & Akagi Shinto shrine to enjoy Japanese traditional music & dance performances.

2:00-4:00pm (and beyond) : Walking around Kagurazaka town and streets to enjoy the historical atmosphere & performances.

There will be a grand finale performance at the Kaguraden Stage of Akagi Shrine from around 5:30-7:30 pm, and other performances going into the evening, so please check the schedule for exact performance times!*

* Official event page with schedule: https://kaguramachi.jp/en/

Map of Kagurazaka with attractions of the event:
https://kaguramachi.jp/pdf/2019timeschedule.pdf

【Event Fee】FREE!

【Meeting place & time】At 1:00pm near Iidabashi station

=> Exact meeting place on Google map:

https://goo.gl/maps/nzR8eQA65HdkPzNC6

--------------------------------
Charms of Kagurazaka
--------------------------------
In the 17th century, Kagurazaka developed as a residential district for “Samurai” soldiers, along the main street which crossed the outer moat and connected Edo castle with residences of the nobility.

Since then it's also been a district of performing arts with traditional music instruments, where a number of culturati loved and lived.

The Karyukai (*) was born here at the end of the Edo period, and flourished in the following decades. Especially in the early Showa period (1925 -mid 1930s), the district had some department stores lined up and was so called “Ginza of Yamanote,” a top hilside commercial district.

*Karyukai: A society or physical district of Geisha Ladies – who have trained manners and skills of traditional music and dancing, and Ryotei - where Geisha Ladies present traditional performances during fine Japanese multi-course dinners.

The district was completely destroyed by the air raids in the WW II, but rather quickly restored its prosperity by the 1960s. In recent years, the Karyukai has scaled down, yet we still find the district of Ryotei, where stone-paved alleys & black-board walls are laid out, the sounds of laughter, and shamisen, a traditional music instrument, flowing over.

Kagurazaka also hosts many French residents and restaurants which creates an atmosphere somewhat like the back alleys in Paris, adding another charm. Such diversity, and harmony between the old and new, attracts many people!

PLEASE NOTE:

If you smoke, please do so only in designated smoking areas.

Your comments and suggestions for future meetups are always welcome!

Thanks!

Your event organizer, Kerry D. @}:^)

how_to_find_us: Get off at Exit A1, Tsim Sha Tsui MTR Station. Walk on Haiphong Road behind you and meet at the Kowloon Park entrance.
name: Off-Camera Flash Headshots - Free Tutorial - 1pm - Sunday 12th May 2019
group_name: JPG Photography Meetup Group - Hong Kong
description:
Portrait shoot practice time, folks!
Ever since you bought your new camera and an off-camera flash, you could never find an opportunity to use them. Well, here's your chance to do some portrait shots with them. Fashion and portrait photography is my day job and I can show you how it's done.

Using one speed light in portrait photography can get you great results but only if you know how to do it. We're here to show you how. It's really easy.

We're only taking upper body shots so you won't need anything fancy. You may already have invested in a speed light, soft box and radio trigger. We'll show you how to use all of them and, by the end of the day, you'll be surprised at the results! You'll learn how to position the light, how to pose your subject and in just 5 hours of practice, you'll become quite good at it.

And best of all, this tutorial is free! So come to Kowloon Park at 1pm after you have your quick lunch. Or pack your lunch and eat in the park.

How to find us:
If you come by MTR, get off at Tsim Sha Tsui and look for Exit A1. After you exit on the ground level you'll be facing Nathan Road (full of people and traffic). As you stand there, next to your right is Haiphong Road. Turn right and walk back on Haiphong Road and look for the Kowloon Park gate entrance. You'll see a wide sloping pathway. All of us will be there waiting. Don't be late. After the shoot, we'll all go for tea and coffee and compare photos.

Watch this video of our previous event: https://youtu.be/4ar3FOyHsdE

We'll be split into groups of 3 people. One to shoot, one to hold the light and one to model. We'll switch and take turns.
I'll first give a demo to everyone when we meet. After that, I'll go around to each group and check on your camera settings, lights and guide you all on the shots.

What to bring:
1. A camera with a flash hot shoe.
2. A radio trigger for triggering your flash. (Godox, Pocket Wizard,
ProPhoto, Yongnuo, Flashpoint, etc)
3. A speed light that works with your camera and trigger. (Canon, Nikon,
etc)
4. A small soft box or light modifier. (A white shoot through umbrella will
do)
5. A light stand. (to mount your flash and light modifier)

But if you don't have all these, just bring a camera and a reflector. The reflector will help tremendously in your shots.

Note: All of you will take turns being models. So dress nice and put on your makeup. Bring some accessories like sunglasses, hats, etc. Yeah, the men, too! We're only shooting upper body - from waist up.

See all of you there, folks! Don't be late!

name: Photo Walk at Deene Park Northants
description:
You are invited to attend a Photo Walk at Dean Park http://deenepark.com the beautiful home of the Brudenell family situated in the stunning countryside of East Northamptonshire, 18 minutes South West of Stamford. Deene Park is a Tudor and Georgian Mansion, developed and owned by the Brudenell family since 1514. Deene was the seat of the Earls of Cardigan, of whom the most notable was the 7th Earl who led the charge of the Light Brigade at Balaklava in 1854. The Post Code is NN17 3EW and the location is on the A43 Stamford to Corby road, soon after the Bulwick turning. Meet in the carpark, which is signposted & situated close to the house, adjacent to the river at 14.00. Photography is allowed in the Gardens, in the surrounding grounds (which are extensive & very well maintained) and in the Courtyard area & externally of the house. Photography is not permitted inside the house, as it is occupied, but entrance to this house is an option (last entrance 16.00) at additional expense - check website for details. I recommend the Queens Head at Bulwick, just off the A43 to the left (approaching from Stamford) if you fancy lunch before or a drink afterwards http://www.queensheadbulwick.com looking forward to seeing you there. Everyone welcome & assistance will be available for beginners, from the more experienced members attending.
They have a nice coffee shop, so suggest we have a review of the trip in there at 16.00.

name: Stoney Hill Trail
description:
The Stoney Hill trail is rated as an easy 3.7 km loop, located near North Cowichan. It has a few, rather wonderful views. This is an afternoon event so that the sun will be behind us for optimal photos.

Getting There:
The point on the map is pretty accurate, as I recall. Allow sufficient time to get there. If you're in Nanaimo, I'd allow an hour and 15 minutes at the very least. If you'd like to carpool, feel free to post a message and coordinate with other members.

Suggested Gear:
Any camera, including a phone, will do.

Important to Know:
Although an easy trail, this is still a hike, so proper hiking footwear is highly recommended. In addition to uneven ground, you will encounter tree roots and loose/slippery ground (dirt, gravel, rocks, etc.). This hike will also bring you to the unprotected edge of several cliffs (although you can easily keep your distance and still get good photos).

Always watch your step and DO NOT move your feet while looking through your camera.

Disclaimer/Waiver:
You, and your guests, must read and agree to the contents of this linked document before joining this activity... https://www.meetup.com/VI_Photowalks/pages/26958864/Disclaimer_and_Waiver

This photowalk will be rescheduled if continuous rain is in the forecast.

This event requires AT LEAST 5 committed members be in attendance.

RSVP:
If you have RSVP'd to the walk and decide not to attend, please change your RSVP. We do check the RSVP's remotely for changes (right up to departure time) and wait for members to arrive, but out of respect to those attending, we want to start the walk as promptly as possible.

how_to_find_us: Room 111
name: Lightroom Workshop (beginners/intermediate)
description:
Do you ever ask yourself: Why do my photos look so dull and flat? Why are my images so dark? Well, Lightroom can fix that! Aimed for beginners and intermediate users, this 2.5 hr-workshop will cover the essentials of the photo-editing software Lightroom and introduce some new features offered by Lightroom Classic CC. Some topics that will be covered are:

✓ Global adjustments (exposure, contrast, color corrections, fixing perspectives, etc)
✓ Local adjustments (color / luminance range masking, dehaze)
✓ Using tone curves
✓ Creating a panorama / HDR image
✓ Basic landscape / portrait editing

For this workshop you will need to bring with you:
1. A laptop computer + charger
2. Pre-installed Lightroom Classic CC or Lightroom 6
Link to 7-day trial version of Classic CC version: https://creative.adobe.com/de/products/download/lightroom-classic
3. (Optional) Some of your own photos in RAW format

The workshop costs 5 EUR to cover the venue and the equipment rental. You are also welcome to leave a small tip of an additional few Euros if you enjoyed the workshop. :)

We look forward to seeing you there!

Extra info: A few days before the meet up we will send a link to all confirmed participants with the exercise files that we will work on together during the workshop. So please don't forget to check your message inbox, thanks.

name: Reflections, Sunsets and Symmetry at Bosham Quay
description:
WHAT IT IS

Degree of difficulty - 3 (easy)

This is an on location mentoring session. Its designed to be fun and not as formal as that sounds ...... for up to six people, the day starts with a challenge, followed by 1:1 mentoring and ending up the day watching (and photographing) the sunset. More details below :)

The session is all about looking for, finding and using reflections, sunsets and symmetry in your photography

One of the places which is good for sunsets and reflections (not sure I can find an ideal place for all three) is Bosham Harbour. With its large expanse of sheltered and relatively flat water at high tide, its very good for reflections of Bosham Quay, and good too for sunsets as they reflect too …..

LOGISTICS

We will meet in Bosham Quay car park at 18.30 and walk around the inland harbour to its south side. Opportunities for reflections and symmetries are all around, and at the south side of the harbour we will wait for sunset at 20.45. High water neaps is 19.00. A postcode very near the car park is PO18 8HT. Its easy to find. There are charges but they wont break the bank.

Pray for some quiet weather and some high level cloud for the sunset and we could get some very striking images indeed.

The walk there and back is around 1.5km in length. Its flat …..

If time at the end of the event allows, we will drop into the Blue Anchor for a chat, debrief and a packet of crisps .....

HOW WILL WE KNOW IF IT IS GOING AHEAD?

Just about the only reason to cancel the event is if there is a reasonable chance of rain. I will get a very good idea two-three days ahead of the event and cancel, if appropriate, at that point. If I cancel I will offer refunds :)

If we are going ahead then I will send out an A4 training sheet giving details about the compositional techniques involved. Look out for it!

WHO IS THIS FOR?

As its about one of the basics of composition its for anyone who wishes to improve their photography. It does not matter at all what camera or mobile camera you have, nor what settings you choose to use.

Beginners and improvers benefit, and I’ve begun to realise that many of those who consider themselves experienced can benefit. My photography too has improved since starting the sessions …..

ESSENTIALS AND ADMIN DETAILS

My phone number in case you get lost (it happens!) is[masked].

Bring a torch and wear Wellies. Bring an extra layer of clothing, it can get colder towards sunset

Any other questions, fire away in the comments section!

Andy :)

name: Wonders of Chile & Patagonia
description:
May 12th-May 19th 2019
Our friends at PhotoFly Travel Club ( http://www.photoflytravel.com/ ) have invited us to another amazing adventure in Chile & Patagonia!
E-mail [masked] for the DAILY ITINERARY!
Sign up at: http://www.photoflytravel.org/chile-group-tour-santiago-patagonia/
Our Chile group tour is one of our most exciting adventures in style! This epic journey will begin in the world renowned capital of Santiago where we will enjoy the culture, food, and energy of the bustling city among the mountains. Unforgettable hikes & photographs will be the norm throughout this adventure with activities available for all fitness levels!
Email to see daily itinerary at [masked]
---------------------
* 7 night/8 Day Journey (2 Nights Santiago, 5 Nights Patagonia)
---------------------
Santiago

* Centrally located and welcoming Santiago accommodations
* Breakfast & Lunch everyday
* 5 Dinners Included
* Unique culinary experience with Uncorked (Guided food shopping experience at local markets, Chef instructed cooking of our own lunch Santiago style, Enjoy delicious self prepared lunch with local Pisco Sour cocktail)
*Free time in Santiago to explore the city & photograph the sites
-----------------
Patagonia
* Patagonia Camp is the first Luxury Camp in South America. It is an original and distinctive glamping concept where every detail has been carefully thought of so that our guests may thoroughly enjoy the magnificent and wild nature of mythical Patagonia, combining comfort, convenience, and the warm hospitality that Chileans are known for.
* All Inclusive Meals & Adventures while at Patagonia Camp. Plus Open Bar throughout!
* One of a kind luxury yurt style accommodations at Patagonia Camp
* Each day we will have the opportunity to embark on amazing walks and hikes around this wonderland landscape of sharp edged mountains and glacier lakes. See below for JUST A FEW OF THE HIKES AND ADVENTURES that we’ll be able to choose from each day (all are optional, included, and cater to different fitness levels including beginners!)
Base of the Towers Trek: A rewarding & deservedly famous trek to the base of the iconic “Towers” of Torres Del Paine. Panoramic views of lakes and valleys greet us along the way until we penetrate the ancient lenga tree forest.
Los Cuernos Trek: This trek is perfect to experience the beauty of the park’s two iconic mountains: Las Torres and Los Cuernos del Paine. The hike starts alongside beautiful rivers and lakes with ever-present native flora and fauna.
Mirador Condor Hike: The hike to the Cóndor viewpoint is another privileged trek in terms of views. The trail begins at Lake Pehoé which will fascinate our eyes and cameras with its distinctive turquoise color. You will climb for about an hour through the Sierra del Toro; along the way you can appreciate some of the local vegetation such as nothofagus trees, the area’s micro-wildlife and the beautiful soaring condors.
*Optional horseback riding & boat trips will be available at additional price. *minimum # sign ups needed
------------------
Inclusions:
* Privately guided small group tour as always!
* All Taxes & Entrance Fees included
* All Transfers and ground transportation included
* Roommate Pairing to save money as always!
* Domestic round-trip airfare from Santiago –> Punta Arenas INCLUDED
* International Airfare is not included but we will assist all guests with finding the best flight!
(Specific arrival/departure times will be sent to all guests and we’ll assist in booking the proper flights as always)
* Email us to see daily itinerary at [masked]

name: Weekly Photo Project - Perspective
description:
Every week we will have a different prompt for our weekly photo project. This week’s theme is Perspective.

Each week beginning early Monday morning, you can begin uploading your photos to our meetup album for the week’s theme. The group won’t actually meet for this event, it’s an individual online challenge for each of you to get your creative juices flowing, share photos in the group, comment and critique each other’s shots, and above all have fun.

Albums will remain open, so you can upload photos any time after that Monday morning start time but you’ll get the most feedback during the initial week the theme is posted. You also don’t have to restrict yourself to photos taken during that week for the theme, they can be from past shoots you have done or the weekly prompt can be used to motivate you to shoot something new.

We also have a Facebook group (https://www.facebook.com/groups/ericleuthardtphotography.club/) that you are encouraged to share your photos in.

name: Getting Started with Studio Lighting - PPA Super 1-Day Workshop
description:
I have been selected as a Professional Photographers of America (PPA) Super 1-day Workshop Host. Enrollment will be done on the PPA website. See the link below. If you have issues registering on the PPA website, please contact us - [masked] or[masked].

Here is the official write up:

This program will begin with the instructor, Robert DiTommaso, CPP, explaining each of the aspects that go into achieving the correct lighting. This includes using strobes and a light meter, and knowing how to properly use them to your advantage. There will be several lighting kits onsite for you to work in teams to use. You will unbox, assemble, and shoot with the lights to get comfortable handling equipment.
Later in the class, Robert will include umbrellas, soft boxes, and battery powered strobes. This will allow you to become educated on the variety of lighting options available, and begin to choose the gear that will work best for you and the outcome you desire for your work. If there is time, you will also explore working with multiple lights to make a white backdrop appear white, gray, or even black.

Items to Bring: Camera, lens(es), laptop (optional), handouts will be provided.

Link to enroll...filter for Michigan and the workshop will pop right up.

https://www.ppa.com/events/super-one-day/find-a-super-1-day-class-near-you

name: Scavenger Hunt aboard the USS Midway Museum
description:
Come join us for a completely different kind of shoot, a Scavenger Hunt on the USS Midway Museum. your hosts Larry and Walter have uploaded twenty images to the the event album. You will need to find as many as possible of these and take a photo of them and upload it. Whoever gets the most correct will win a prize from George’s Camera, your choice of a Sensor Cleaning or a $50.00 Gift Certificate. In case of a tie, both prizes will be given out.

Admission fee to the USS Midway Museum is $22.00 for adults, $19.00 for seniors and $9.00 for retired military with ID. We highly recommend you buy your tickets online before the event. Otherwise you have to wait in line. Parking is a flat rate of $10.00 per car. Carpooling is recommended.

Special note: The first six members to sign up will get in for free. If any member going is a USS Midway member and can get guests in free, please let us know.

We will meet at the entrance of the USS Midway Museum at 9:30AM and enter promptly at 10:00AM. We will proceed to the Flight Deck first where we will take the group photo. The images you will need to find are spread out in different areas of the ship. You can take as long as you like to find them and enjoy the museum. When you upload the images, please load them all at once so your images are together in the album. This makes it easier for the judges.

Here is a link to the album.

https://www.meetup.com/pacificphoto/photos/29882257/

As for equipment, all the photos uploaded were taken with full frame DSLR’s and 24-70 lenses. This just for your information. You are of course free to use any lens you like.

Please Note: By submitting a YES RSVP and participating in any PPS event, you agree that PPS, Organizers, and Event Hosts are NOT responsible for your safety or for any injury or damage to your person or your property, or that of your guest(s).You agree that you have read the instructions of the announcement and that you and your guest(s) are assuming all risks of participating in the event.

name: The Sound of Your Voice: Sound design demonstration
description:
Joins us for this fascinating look at the creative potential of sound and how it is used to evoke emotion, reflect moods and mark action

With us we will have Hunt Beaty and Emmy Award-winning sound mixer Cory Choy, come join us for a screening of Beaty’s short film The Sound Of Your Voice followed by a Q&A with the director, a sound design demonstration, and a Q&A with the mixer.

Please sign up via Eventbrite: https://www.eventbrite.com/e/the-sound-of-your-voice-sound-design-demonstration-tickets-61104104020

About Cory

A founding member of Silver Sound, Emmy Award-winning Cory Choy has been pushing the audio limits since 2003. He has crisscrossed the globe with the likes of director and activist Iara Lee, explorer and TV host Richard Wiese, and trouble-and-movie-maker Andrew Wonder as a production sound mixer; he has been supervising sound designer for folks such as indie horror legend Lloyd Kaufman and actor/producer Max Casella; and he has mixed countless commercial spots, animations, documentaries and narrative films for people and companies from fine artist Susan Philipsz to director Musa Syeed to NBC. Driven by a desire to excel in his craft and a belief that he can always learn more, Cory has never been afraid to go off the beaten path: he was an early adopter of both Sonic Foundry Vegas and the groundbreaking DAW REAPER from Cockos, has been a proponent of the game-changing Zaxcom Nomad, and is constantly searching for and thinking about new and better ways to record, edit, create, and mix sound.

About Hunt

Hunt Beaty is a producer, director, and Emmy award-winning production sound mixer based in Brooklyn, NY. Born and raised in Nashville, TN and NYU Tisch Film Graduate (and he jumps out of airplanes for fun).
Most recently Hunt embarked on a year-long project to make six short films alongside filmmakers Wesley Wingo and Andres Cardona with the intent of reinvigorating their “narrative muscles,” so to speak. The team rotated the director role with each project and released the films online as fast as possible. The shorts earned thousands of views, multiple Vimeo staff picks, and a slot in the 2019 SXSW film festival.

Check them all out here: www.sixshortfilms.com
