name: Manchester Fashion Week Opening Night Show 2019
description:
Thanks to Amanda from Manchester fashion week for setting us all up with a maximum of 50 spaces.

How it all works:
All posts published to social media must use

#manchesterfashionweek
@manchesterfw

Please tag us as well with:
@igersmcr
#igersmcr_fashionweek

Entry to the show:
Wrist bands will be given to those who sign up through the meetup page and follow the link below and select a blogger from the options.

How to get your ticket:
Please go to this event page and select a blogger ticket from the options. Make sure to show your attendance from this meet up when asked at the event as proof you're an Instagram blogger. Just in case you have any self-doubts everyone in this meetup group is classed as a blogger and by posting event pics to Instagram/facebook/twitter... Etc

https://www.eventbrite.co.uk/e/manchester-fashion-week-opening-night-tickets-54153232777

Photography rules:
No photos of children are allowed!

Event Details:

With just a few weeks to go till Manchester’s finest fashion show the Manchester Fashion Week, designers are preparing for the most diverse showcase.

The show, which takes place on the roof terrace at Hotel Football on 13 May, will be split into two parts, with the first part focusing on street and urban style led by Gogairy Hand Painted Leathers, an artist turned fashion designer who, as the title suggests,paints exquisite bespoke designs onto leather or vegan leather jackets turning them into personal cherished masterpieces.

Twisted Couture is a brand new edgy label from Manchester which strives to break any from the stereotypical high street norm

The BeesKnees Boutique offers an alternative collection of prom and wedding dresses, stoking corsets and genderless outfits and are one of the main dressers for costumes for Manchester Pride

Kintsugi appeals to everyone, literally, as an all-inclusive brand specialising in tailored pieces for able-bodied women and those in wheelchairs and with prosthetic limbs, giving them easy access to wearing on-trend items to make them feel elegant and well groomed.

The second half will focus on haute couture from designer around the world who have settled in Manchester and grown their businesses with locally sourced textiles, reminding the industry of the north west’s rich cultural heritage. Tehran bird Nooshin uses her rich heritage of fabrics and textures to create show-stopping outfits which are a canvas for artistic beauty

Flenci Rose returns to the catwalk for the second year running to showcase her bright Zimbabwe- inspired brightly coloured fabrics and clean-cut suits and dresses.

The show’s finale is Be Unique Be You, quite fitting for the name which represents the ethos of the show

Director Amanda Moss said, "Manchester Fashion Week symbolises everything that fashion is all-out; empowering, inclusive and all-encompassing. People shouldn't have to go to London when the north of the Uk has always been the centre of fashion with its rich textile industry. North West really is best."

Also expected to report on the high profile event is Fashion TV who will broadcast the show on the channel around the world.

Manchester Fashion Week also features a free hair styling workshop in between the catwalk shows from sponsor Pierre Alexandre.

name: Metropolis by Fritz Lang - SOLD OUT
description:
A sprawling city lies at the heart of legendary director Fritz Lang’s vision of 2027: one where the wealthy cruise around in flying automobiles, languish in towering penthouses, and cavort in lush gardens far above the ground. Meanwhile, far below, the denizens of the dismal workers’ city struggle to survive every day. Unrest between the disillusioned working class and society’s elite reaches its breaking point when Freder, the son of the city’s richest and most powerful man, becomes aware of the inhumane conditions under which the working class must exist. As he falls in love with Maria, who preaches to the workers about a better world in which the “head” and “hands” of the city live side-by-side, Freder is determined to become the “heart” that brings these two groups together. What he is not prepared for is the chaos that this mission will unleash. Will he manage to unite these two opposing forces, or will the city fall to ruin?

A silent film with a sweeping score, Metropolis was one of the first science-fiction films in cinema. Its futuristic aesthetic continues to inspire countless filmmakers and artists, as do its powerful messages about the importance of mutual respect and understanding among people.

An introduction to the film will be provided by Dr. Peter Pfeiffer, Professor of German and Director of the European Studies Certificate Program at Georgetown University. A discussion will follow the screening.

The Goethe Institut USA in Washington, DC is showing this German Expressionist classic as part of their "Wunderbar: A Celebration of German Film" series.

Seating is SOLD OUT. If you don't already have your ticket, we're sorry to say that you won't be able to come.

Directed by Fritz Lang. Screenplay by Thea von Harbou and Fritz Lang.
Weimar Republic (Germany), 1927, 148 min., silent film with German and English intertitles.

name: May MPC Education Night - Stephen Johnson "Other Worldly"
venue_name: Corte Madera Town Center Community Room
description:
Stephen Johnson - Presenter

Presentation: Other Worldly

Steve will discuss his exhibition of new prints from over 50 years of Space Photography joining the current Life Form Exhibition for a mind-blowing journey from the living world close-up viewpoint to the depths of space. The Space Exhibit evolved out of his longterm interest in the space program and views offered by the heavens and by spacecraft far away. The concentration on the exotic form of the living world of the Life Form work inspired this expressive look at the wonders of the very large and distant in this print exploration of photographs Steve has been gathering for years.

Biography:
Website: www.stephenjohnson.photography

Stephen Johnson concentrates on landscape projects exploring wild, endangered spaces and human-altered lands, making images that depict a respect for the land and a real-world celebration of our relationship to nature.

He has long been admired for his high photographic craft and for his dedication to making fine prints, excelling at sharing his knowledge and passion for our medium with countless individuals. He is the creator of touring exhibitions, five books, three portfolios and has been teaching photography since 1978.

Johnson has worked with Adobe and many other industry leaders on expanding and refining the tools we use as photographers. He was named to the Photoshop Hall of Fame in 2003, as an ‘Explorer of Light’ by Canon in 2006, and lectures at leading industry seminars and universities as well as mentoring a select group of aspiring artists.

In 1999, Folio Magazine declared the publication of Johnson's digital photographs in Life Magazine to be one of the Top 15 Critical Events in magazine publishing in the twentieth century.

name: FREE Lightroom Class at Ross Norton Community Center — Class 2 of 8
venue_address_1: 1426 S Martin Luther King Jr Avenue
description:
The return of the FREE Lightroom classes at Ross Norton Recereation Complex

What better way to learn and improve your Lightroom skills than in a relaxed atmosphere. This was an informal study group that has transitioned to a formal evening class. It has an anounced topic and structure each night.

Every Monday night the instructor will teach for two hours in a formal manner using his laptop and projector, as illustrated above. Every module will be covered over the course of several months.

Want additional help or have questions that weren't answered in class? Please consider joining us at FCCP After Dark, just down the street, at O'Keefe's Family Restaurant in Clearwater.

What FCCP Members are saying about the class.

Jeff explains Lightroom patiently, in a logical sequence, and with strict clarity. He continually checks for understanding, and dignifies all questions. His sense of humor puts everyone at ease . . . . . . Cade

Great class and great studio! I love learning in depth how a program works, so this class was spot on. I will be there next week! . . . . . . Kelly

Great group of people, great teacher & a comfortable, quiet meeting site! . . . Jane

I have had good instructors in the past, but Jeff Donald is by far the best. He speaks clearly and loudly, he knows his subject, he knows what is important to cover, he stays on task, he repeatedly asks for questions, he is friendly, he has a sense of humor, and he is everyone’s idea of a leader. . . . . . There will be lots of learning and laughter. Jeff Donald will teach each session and he's a certified Lightroom teacher, having taught every version since the first beta version in 2007. Jeff worked for Apple Computer until 2009 and worked with 1,000's of customers during that time. Experienced members will be on hand to share tips & tricks and more.

name: Smith Rock Summit Loop/7.4 mi @1664 e.g./Moderate
group_name: Oregon Adventures, outdoor activities and more
description:
HIKE OVERVIEW

Hello Hikers/ Outdoor Adventurists! It is my great pleasure to have Smith Rock Park nearly in my backyard and because of that convenience, I would like to propose the Summit Loop as a repeat hike so you can count on it once a month on the second Tuesday at 10 am. I'll meet you at the yurt at the park!

HIKE DETAILS

* MODERATE/DIFFICULT 7.4 mile loop, 1664 elevation gain
* Pace: Slow - 1.5 - 2mph - lots of opportunity for enjoying nature & pictures
* Pack the Ten Essentials; Lunch; Trail Snacks; Plenty of Water
* I recommend sturdy hiking boots & poles
* Wear non-cotton layers & bring rain gear
* Carpool from TBD...use the message board to arrange
* Drive time to Terrebonne: @ 40 min.
* Permits or Parking Fees: $5 day use fee- they have fee stations which take credit cards

We will hike the 7 mi. Summit Trail Loop. From the park we will hike down into the canyon and follow along the Crooked River (Wolf Creek trail) until the Burma Rd. section where we will hike a 855 ft. eg for @ 1 mi. This can be a thigh-burner, but the views of the top make it well worth while. This trail is well maintained but does have an uneven rocky surface. From the top we can stop, take in the views!! and have lunch/snack. From there we will head down the Summit trail (a switchback scree trail -poles are a plus here) and cross a short section of private property before reconnecting with the River trail. This part of the "loop"will give us an up close view of the famous Monkey Face pillar.

WHAT TO BRING:
* Pack the Ten Essentials;
• Lunch; Trail Snacks; Plenty of Water
• I recommend sturdy hiking boots & poles
• Wear non-cotton layers & bring rain gear

CARPOOLING:
• We will carpool from - TBD
Once members have RSVP'd you can make arrangements through the message board on our meetup site.

I WILL MEET YOU AT THE YURT (ranger station) AT THE PARK . . . ON THE LEFT AS YOU APPROACH THE PARK

------------ DRIVING DIRECTIONS -----------------------------

TIME: @ 40 min. From Bend

Drive ...Take Hwy 97 North ...From 97 take a Right turn onto Smith Rock Way. Follow the signs from there.

name: Figure Drawing / Painting (Drop-In)
description:
Drop-In every Tuesday 6-8pm

Price: $12 (drop-in);
Card of 10 sessions $100 Includes Model Fee

We alternate between traditional life drawing sessions with a nude model and vogue style figure painting sessions with a semi-nude or costume.

You are welcome to draw or paint. Easels or tables are provided.

The best way to learn how to draw anything is by observing and drawing human beings. If you know how to render the figure well, your skills at creating nonfigurative and even abstract art will be stronger. Life drawing teaches accuracy of observation and leads to the ability to draw or paint any subject.

The more you draw the figure the more you will develop the ability to communicate movement and personality. By using simple lines an artist should be able to give a figure a real sense of life and individuality. You will learn to draw three dimensionally and to make the figures feel like they exist in a real world.

- Nude, semi-nude or costumed model.
- We begin with short poses suitable for gesture drawing and build up to longer half-hour poses.
- Multiple light source so you don't end up in the dark.
- Assistance is available but no instruction, peer review only.
- Wine is welcome (bring your own or share with a friend)

Price: $12 (drop-in);
Card of 10 sessions $100
A card guarantees you a spot!

REGISTER HERE http://www.swintonsart.com/index.php/instruction/figure-drawing-painting

IMPORTANT NOTE:

Our classes are very popular and fill up quickly. We encourage you to REGISTER. If you purchased a card your spot is guaranteed. For everyone else, we urge you to

REGISTER
http://www.swintonsart.com/index.php/instruction/figure-drawing-painting

for any class you wish to attend. Otherwise, it's first come first serve and you may be turned away.

name: Introduction to Food Photography
description:
Before attending this Meetup, you must first pay & register here:
(https://www.precision-camera.com/introduction-to-food-photography/)

Learn the basics of food photography. This class will cover key concepts to help you take mouth-watering photos of food and is geared towards all skill levels and users of all cameras, including mobile phones, point and shoot, mirrorless and DSLRs.

Concepts Covered
• Types of food photography vary: blogging, informal social media, editorial, and commercial
• Overview of good food photography
• Successful shooting angles, macro, close-up, overhead, 45 degree dining angle
• Food styling basics
• Plating/prop styling
• Composition
• Working with continuous light

Supplies Needed
• Camera
• Any lenses you wish to use
• A fully-charged camera battery
• A memory card with room to take additional pictures
• Note-taking supplies
• Tripod (optional)

Audience
This class is perfect for food bloggers, social media and marketing coordinators, small business owners with a food-related business, editorial photographers, aspiring professional food photographers and any other photographers looking to improve their food photography.

Schedule and Format
This is a three-hour class with one 15 minute break after the first hour. The class is formatted as a slide-based presentation and review of images, a demonstration of some tools of the trade and some hands-on shooting. This class serves as the foundation for the Advanced Food Photography Class.

About the Instructor
Josh Baker, founder of AzulOx Visuals, has photographed food and drinks for clients such as: Patron, Texas de Brasil, Sagra Italian, Catering with a Twist among other food and editorial clients. See more at azuloxcommercial.com.

name: Member Meeting & Watercolor Painting
description:
Boulder Art Association May Member Meeting
Watercolor Painting

Please join us on Tuesday, May 14th, for this fun & creative event!
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
DATE & TIME:
Tuesday, May 14th, 2019
6:00 pm – 8:00 pm

LOCATION:
Alfalfa’s Market – Boulder Community Room
1651 Broadway, Boulder, CO

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
MEETING AGENDA:
– Quick Introductions, Announcements
– Watercolor Painting with Nancy Sullo

Please join us for a fun evening of watercolor painting with Nancy Sullo. Nancy will demonstrate some of her techniques and give you an
opportunity to paint along. The subject will be a light-filled landscape, and the emphasis will be on shapes, values, and simplifying. This
program will be suitable for both experienced watercolor painters AND people new to the medium.You can check out Nancy’s work at www.nancysullowatercolors.com.

If you are already a water colorist, please bring your usual supplies.
For anyone new, supplies will be provided for a small fee of $5 ($10 non-member). Materials supplied will include a 1/4 sheet of professional watercolor paper, use of a palette with paint in it, and use of brushes. Please bring a rag, water container, and apron or paint shirt to protect clothing if you wish.

PARKING: Please DON’T park in Alfalfa’s parking areas. Parking is available in the City of Boulder parking lots across Arapahoe or at the Boulder Public Library. Parking is free for the first 90 minutes in library parking lot (just enter your license plate # into the kiosk). Payment is only metered until 7pm.

More information is available on the Boulder Art Association website https://boulderartassociation.org/may-2019member-meeting-watercolor/

----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
BAA Membership is not required to attend, but if you’d like to become a BAA Member, please join on our Membership Page. https://boulderartassociation.org/membership/

name: May Monthly Meeting - Michael Blanchette  "Backlight - The Beauty and the Beast"
description:
Shooting into the sun holds potential for making dramatic images, especially when it involves a colorful sky. But the high dynamic range of a backlit scene can also pose tedious challenges in post-processing. Backlight is one of Mike’s favorite light sources. In this presentation, he will showcase some of his backlit photos, explain how he took them, and discuss his workflow for yielding balanced exposures.

Michael Blanchette is a New England Photographer who leads workshops, takes amazing images and has spoken to the club before. It's a meeting not to be missed.

Mike's website can be viewed here: http://www.michaelblanchette.com/

Doors open at 6pm - come meet and chat with your fellow camera club members - Programs start at 6:30 sharp and we finish up around 8:15 or so.

name: History Book Club: Mary McGrory: First Queen of Journalism
description: This month we'll get a nice blend - a bit of biography, women's history, journalism history, and mid-to-late 20th century American political history. Here is what the publisher says about the book: "Before there was Maureen Dowd or Gail Collins or Molly Ivins, there was Mary McGrory. She was a trailblazing columnist who achieved national syndication and reported from the front lines of American politics for five decades. From her first assignment reporting on the Army–McCarthy hearings to her Pulitzer-winning coverage of Watergate and controversial observations of President Bush after September 11, McGrory humanized the players on the great national stage while establishing herself as a uniquely influential voice."

name: Meet the Talent #13
description:
Meet the Talent, le rendez-vous des créatifs !

⚠️ INSCRIPTION OBLIGATOIRE ⇢https://www.eventbrite.fr/e/billets-meet-the-talent-13-60571945319 ⚠️

Pour cette nouvelle édition en collaboration avec Adobe France, nous avons sélectionné des talents inspirants qui viendront présenter le(s) projet(s) de leur choix sur un format simple et court.

⚡️Yohan Quintar alias LightOn, Illustrateur et directeur artistique pour différentes campagnes publicitaires, puise son inspiration à la fois dans la culture Hip-Hop, puisqu'il est aussi rappeur, l’art grec antique et la culture Pop. Ses illustrations hautes en couleurs, offrent un regard déshumanisé et corrosif sur la vie urbaine.

⚡️Marie-Laure Cruschi, alias Cruschiform, est une jeune artiste française vivant entre Paris et Montréal. Son travail se situe au carrefour de l’art, du graphisme, de l’illustration et de la typographie. Particulièrement sensible à la couleur et aux formes géométriques, Cruschiform aime expérimenter des dispositifs graphiques à la fois ludiques et poétiques afin de créer des univers narratifs délicats et surprenants.

⚡️Aurélien Jeanney est directeur artistique et designer pluridisciplinaire. Sa pratique traverse plusieurs champs et médiums, de l’illustration, en passant par l’image animée ou la typographie. Il a fondé Maison Tangible, manufacture d'images et d'objets graphiques, devenue galerie d'arts à Paris. Son travail a été récompensé à l’international, notamment avec des prix au Canada (Grafika, Numix) ou en France (Cannes Lions). Et son projet de recherche autour de Jules Verne a reçu une bourse du Ministère de la Culture.

Le travail de chacun de nos trois talents est l'expression d'univers singuliers, en phase avec leur personnalité. Ils nous ouvrent les portes de mondes colorés, expressifs et perpétuellement réinventés.

Nous explorerons les dernières nouveautés avec l’équipe d’Adobe France.

De la bonne humeur, des techniques créatives et du partage autour de pizzas et de bières de 19h à 22h.

En attendant de vous retrouver nombreux, #SaveTheDate, mardi 14 mai prochain !

name: Ballantyne Photography Club Monthly Meeting
description:
7pm: Mix and mingle

7.15: Review of submitted photos: Wildlife/animals

7.45: Speaker: Rick Beldegreen

Wildlife Photography - The Arctic to Antartica and Points beyond

Rick is a local Charlotte veterinarian (mostly retired) and wildlife photographer. He has traveled from the Arctic to Antarctica and many places in between to photograph wildlife in their natural habitats. Wildlife photography often entails experiencing unpleasant photo shooting conditions such as extreme cold or heat, driving rain or snow, mud, mosquitoes and more. I find that this often adds to the drama of the images and also helps tell the story of how these animals survive and even thrive under some of the most inhospitable conditions on earth.

I hope that some of my images help to encourage people to understand the need to preserve and conserve the beauty and wildlife that exists on this planet.

8.45: Q&A and close

Please send ONE image on this month's topic to [masked]. Make your image between 500kb and 1MB in size to arrive no later than midnight on May 13, 2019.

Please remember that our submission challenge is supposed to get you OUT taking NEW photos, not trawling through your old ones! So go take better photos from the things you're learning :)

name: Tuscany, Italy, during height of red poppy season
description:
A Tuscany photography workshop should be at the top of every photographer’s wish list. The landscape is special, the light is legendary, villages are glorious, people are friendly and then there’s the wine. And there is no better time to photograph Tuscany than in late spring when fields are ablaze with red poppies.

https://lorenphotos.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/unnamed-file-500x250.jpgJoin professional photographersRon Lake (http://ronlake.com/)andLoren Fisher (https://lorenphotos.com/about-loren-fisher-photographer/)for a special Tuscany photography workshop as we explore the beauty of Italy’s countryside, medieval villages and spend a day in Florence. Benefit from Ron and Loren’s experience to make unforgettable photos of the diverse Tuscany area including Chianti vineyards, medieval villages, rolling hills and of course, those red poppies.

We take care of all the details, once you arrive in Rome, you don’t need to think about where to go, how to get there or where to stay during the eight days and seven nights we are in Italy. Just show up and be ready to have fun and make great images.

You will get professional photography instruction from experienced pros Loren Fisher and Ron Lake, who have helped photographers improve their images for years. Our group will be small so you will have plenty of time with each pro giving you advice on composition, angle and lens selection to help you get the best pictures possible not only while you are in Tuscany but long afterward. We will work with you as much as you want at every location.

https://lorenphotos.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Tre-Lampade5635-500x250.jpgWe start with dinner in Rome, but you are free to explore the city during the day if your flight arrives early that morning. We’ll be at the hotel so you can drop off your luggage and we’ll help organize an excursion into the city or enjoy the hotel’s beautiful pool. There is a shuttle from the hotel into Rome which makes getting to the main sights easy. Bright and early the next morning we head north to Tuscany stopping in medieval villages, lush countrysides glowing with red poppies, vineyards and a day in Florence.

The full itinerary is below and you can see it is packed with tremendous locations with plenty of beautiful towns and countryside to photograph. While we want to see it all, we don’t want to wear anyone out. As photographers, we love the morning light so we will be out shooting at sunrise most days. We will take two to three hour breaks from shooting at mid-day as needed, when the light isn’t as nice to catch a nap or refresh. Each day either Ron or Loren will be available during these mid-day breaks for image review or work with you on your photography. You will have time to explore on your own or stick with the group.

What is included: Eight days lodging for seven nights, each photographer has their own room Workshop adventure 2 pro photographers/guides Photo Walks Breakfast most mornings Small group size Four star hotels Local transportation Professional photography instruction What isn’t included: Travel to Italy Lunches and dinners Alcoholic drinks Gratuities Non-meal time snacks and soft drinks Who should Attend Anyone with an interest in Italy, beautiful landscape and historic towns – your photographic experience doesn’t matter. Most of our shooting locations will be in towns where some walking will be required. There won’t be long, strenuous hiking.

Weather May is a very pleasant time to visit Tuscany, when the temperatures warm up and the cloud coverage and rainfall decrease. The average highs are in the 70’s during the daytime and lows in the 50’s after dark.

May 14-22, 2019 Deadline for registration is Jan. 15, 2019

Price

$3,600 includes single occupancy lodging, transportation and professional instruction.

$3,200 for returning clients

Non-photographers: $500 discount if you share a room with a photographer.

The full fee is required 120 days prior to the workshop.

https://lorenphotos.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Verso-La-Ca-Solare-copy-500x331.jpgMaximum group size: 12 Hotels Single occupancy hotel accommodations are included.

Photo Equipment You’ll want to have a wide angle, telephoto and possibly a macro lens. Make sure you have lots of memory cards, spare batteries and charger and maybe a polarizer filter. Since we will do some night photography, you’ll want a sturdy tripod. We also suggest bringing a laptop to download your photos and a way to have a backup, either on the original cards or an external hard drive. If you aren’t absolutely sure of everything that your camera does, bring your instruction manual so we can help you fix any problems.

Dining Breakfast most days is included. If we are out on a sunrise shoot we might not get back to the hotel while they are still serving, on those days you’ll grab something on the road. You are responsible for other dining expenses. We will be on the move but taking breaks to enjoy the scenery, dining and wine.

Itinerary(subject to change) May 15:Arrival in Rome.We will meet at the Golden Tulip Hotel, which is less than 15 minutes from Rome’s Fumicino Airport. Our hotel for the first night is 4-star rated with a fabulous pool, tropical bar and modern rooms. You can relax and unwind to get ready for our great photography experience or spend the day exploring Rome. Our first official get together is 7:00 p.m. for dinner at the poolside restaurant and the best part is dinner in on us!

May 16:We depart early to begin our adventure as we head north to Tuscany. We’ll stop in Sovana, a beautiful ancient village built in the 17th century for our first photo shoot. After a fun lunch we drive to the amazing 18th century winery and hotel. The property has a 600-year-old vineyard and the owners will be waiting for us to sample the estate’s wine and olive oil. This will be home for the next few days and photos in the area abound.

May 17: After an early breakfast at the hotel we will be off to shoot what is known as the Strada Chianti – the road to all the famous vineyard towns. We’ll visit Ron’s favorite, the medieval Chianti town of Castellina in Chianti and also Panzano, Greve in Chianti and tiny Montefioralle. As darkness settles in we’ll have one of our famous tailgate dinners as we wait for the full moon to rise over an ancient hilltop village.

May 18:Today we’re off to Florence. Not only will we photograph the must-see piazzas and other main attractions, we will shoot some of Florence’s lesser known neighborhoods, markets and back streets. After lunch, which will be insanely good if we can get in to the amazing Il Latini, we will shoot from Giotto’s Campanile bell tower down on the Duomo. We make our way back by way of Fiesole which looks out over Florence for the golden hour light.

https://lorenphotos.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/04/Montichiello.pngMay 19:Time to head south to the heart of Tuscany, the Val D‘Orcia region and the famously photogenic rolling hills that surround Pienza and Montepulciano. The fields should be filled with beautiful red poppies. We check in at our new hotel, near the “Centro Storico,” the old town. We’ll visit Montepulciano, which is only five miles away and the S roads of Monticchiello (you know, like in “Under the Tuscan Sun,” with Diane Lane). At night we eat at the “to die for“ Trattoria La Buca delle Fate, one of Ron and Loren’s favorite restaurants in all of Italy.

May 20:Today we are up early for the Tuscan sunrise and then we visit some of Pienza’s neighboring little towns like Chiusi and Montalcino. We will take a long mid-day break so you can catch up on sleep or wander over to the marvelous shops in Pienza’s old town. We’ll have an early dinner at the tiny but special Osteria Sette di Vino before going back out to the countryside for golden hour and sunset. One of the special treats of Pienza is Buon Gusto Gelateria, one of the best gelato places in all of Europe. It is a great way to end the day.

May 21:We head out while it is still dark so we can get to one of Tuscany’s truly special places, Podere Belvedere. You have probably seen photos from there as the sun comes in sideways from the left backlighting the building and cypress trees on a rolling tuscan landscape that many say is unrivaled. Then we go down the road to Cappella della Madonna di Vitaleta, the famous church of Pienza. The little church sits on a hilltop out in the field and it looks great in the morning golden hour light. We’ll go back to Pienza, grab some breakfast and take a little rest before going to Montepulciano for vineyards galore, lunch, shopping, tastings and shooting the old town before heading back for an afternoon break. As the evening light glows, we go back toward Montichiello watching the sunset and then we photograph the “blue hour” and try some light painting.

May 22:Our saddest day, the last one. The hardy will go out and photograph sunrise in the fields below Pienza. After breakfast we head back to Rome to make flight connections.

To register and for more information, go to https://lorenphotos.com/mevents/tuscany-photography-workshop-when-fields-are-filled-with-red-poppies-may-2019/

You must follow the link above to register. Your Meetup RSVP doesn't get you in the workshop. There will be attendees who aren't members of this meetup group.

name: Kevin Dooley - Perfecting Wildlife
description:
Kevin Dooley is an award-winning wildlife and portrait/wedding photographer who grew up in Placitas, New Mexico. The Interest of photography began at an early age of 14 with the Christmas gift of a 35mm camera. Working as an Assistant photographer and darkroom technician in his father's portrait Studio was the beginning of a lifetime career in Photography. At the age of 18, he enlisted in the US Navy and served on an Aircraft carrier. After completing his service he returned to New Mexico and opened his own photography Studio in Albuquerque. During the 37 years the Studio has been in operation it has received numerous awards. His passion for wildlife photography and for Alaska and Africa led to his safari adventures, he eventually opened Idube Photo Safaris. Kevin is a certified FGASA (Field Guide Association of South Africa), wildlife guide and takes guests from all over the world on amazing photographic and sightseeing Safaris in Africa, Alaska, India, South America, and other destinations. He teaches both wildlife photography and portrait photography workshops. Helping both the advanced and the beginner.

https://www.dallasppa.com

name: Digital Training Group
description: Richard Seeley will demonstrate photo editing in Photoshop with emphasis on sharpening and noise reduction

name: Tuscany, Italy, at height of red poppy season
description:
A Tuscany photography workshop should be at the top of every photographer’s wish list. The landscape is special, the light is legendary, villages are glorious, people are friendly and then there’s the wine. And there is no better time to photograph Tuscany than in late spring when fields are ablaze with red poppies.

Join professional photographers Ron Lake (http://ronlake.com/) and Loren Fisher (https://lorenphotos.com/about-loren-fisher-photographer/) for a special Tuscany photography workshop as we explore the beauty of Italy’s countryside, medieval villages and spend a day in Florence. Benefit from Ron and Loren’s experience to make unforgettable photos of the diverse Tuscany area including Chianti vineyards, medieval villages, rolling hills and of course, those red poppies.

We take care of all the details, once you arrive in Rome, you don’t need to think about where to go, how to get there or where to stay during the eight days and seven nights we are in Italy. Just show up and be ready to have fun and make great images.

You will get professional photography instruction from experienced pros Loren Fisher and Ron Lake, who have helped photographers improve their images for years. Our group will be small so you will have plenty of time with each pro giving you advice on composition, angle and lens selection to help you get the best pictures possible not only while you are in Tuscany but long afterward. We will work with you as much as you want at every location.


We start with dinner in Rome, but you are free to explore the city during the day if your flight arrives early that morning. We’ll be at the hotel so you can drop off your luggage and we’ll help organize an excursion into the city or enjoy the hotel’s beautiful pool. There is a shuttle from the hotel into Rome which makes getting to the main sights easy. Bright and early the next morning we head north to Tuscany stopping in medieval villages, lush countrysides glowing with red poppies, vineyards and a day in Florence.

The full itinerary is below and you can see it is packed with tremendous locations with plenty of beautiful towns and countryside to photograph. While we want to see it all, we don’t want to wear anyone out. As photographers, we love the morning light so we will be out shooting at sunrise most days. We will take two to three hour breaks from shooting at mid-day as needed, when the light isn’t as nice to catch a nap or refresh. Each day either Ron or Loren will be available during these mid-day breaks for image review or work with you on your photography. You will have time to explore on your own or stick with the group.

What is included: Eight days lodging for seven nights, each photographer has their own room Workshop adventure 2 pro photographers/guides Photo Walks Breakfast most mornings Small group size Four star hotels Local transportation Professional photography instruction What isn’t included: Travel to Italy Lunches and dinners Alcoholic drinks Gratuities Non-meal time snacks and soft drinks Who should Attend Anyone with an interest in Italy, beautiful landscape and historic towns – your photographic experience doesn’t matter. Most of our shooting locations will be in towns where some walking will be required. There won’t be long, strenuous hiking.

Weather May is a very pleasant time to visit Tuscany, when the temperatures warm up and the cloud coverage and rainfall decrease. The average highs are in the 70’s during the daytime and lows in the 50’s after dark.

May 14-22, 2019 Deadline for registration is Jan. 15, 2019

Price
$3,600 includes single occupancy lodging, transportation and professional instruction.
$3,200 for returning clients
Non-photographers: $500 discount if you share a room with a photographer.

how_to_find_us: We'll be in the back room
name: Seattle Stupid Hackathon Monthly Gathering
description:
Hello!

All are welcome to our events--we invite artists, programmers, comedians, writers, cross-stitchers, and etc. Everyone has something stupid to contribute.

See our website for some past content and our code of conduct:
https://seattlestupidhackathon.github.io/

The plan:
7 pm - Arrive with your stupid ideas and whatever you want to work on and look for a stupid sign. (I.e., bring a laptop and/or art supplies if you think you'll work on something requiring that). Nothing messy. Buy yourself a drink and introduce yourself. Look for a stupid sign.

~7-7:10 - If you have an idea, draw a crappy sketch of your bad idea and/or write a short description. We'll assume anyone can join your project unless you make a note saying otherwise.

~7:10-7:30ish - Presentations of Realized Stupidity. Groups/individuals who worked on projects last time and finished them will give unstructured 2-5 min presentations. If the project is deemed totally useless, all involved will get a stupid sticker.
Projects:
- Mansplaining Twitterbot *on rails* - "Well actually, it's a Mansplaining Twitterbot *on rails*"
- Cat Emulator - Petting a real cat releases endorphins, petting your screen... probably doesn't.
- Karen Smith from Mean Girls bot - predicts the weather using non-weather related data.
- Worm Arm(s) -- Like a vest, but the opposite.

~Afterwards, pm - we'll read through/discuss project ideas that folks submitted earlier. Then people will have the opportunity to cosponsor the stupidest ideas by signing on to them. Folks with ideas that have been co-sponsored can then start recruiting people to their ideas. People can also work on their own ideas alone if they'd prefer, but it's usually more fun to work in a group.

- Until 8:55 - drink plenty of beer/coffee/tea, procrastinate, chat, hang out, make stupid shit with strangers. Don't be too productive. Join our slack channel to coordinate with your group so you can finish over the next few weeks if you don't finish by 8:55pm.

9pm - Ada's closes--time to leave! You can hang out at nearby bars after if you want.

Past previously submitted stupid ideas are on our slack channel: https://join.slack.com/t/stupidslack-seattle/shared_invite/enQtNTc0OTcyNjM0Mzg1LTVjNWI4MmZkM2JlYmMyNTVhMmFhYWQ0Njc5NzVlOGM2MTRlNjIyMTM5N2ZmMDQzNTNjNTA5ZTY0MWUzYmJkZGU

If you have any questions, please comment below, send me a message, or email me at [masked]

Hope to see you there!
Harry

how_to_find_us: We will meet near the restrooms by the parking lot
name: Walking in the woods with cameras
description:
Like going for a walk in the woods? Like photography? Combine the two by joining us for a light walk in the woods at Lansford Canal State Park in Catawba, SC. Every month or so we will gather at a new location and with a new theme to keep us motivated. The Spider Lilies should be out on the Catawba river, and even if they aren't, this is a really cool mix of hiking trails along the river and the remains of an old canal system.

We will leave for a medium length, easy hike at 6:45, and stop at a couple of locations along the way. Expect to walk 3-4 miles, even if its drizzling (if it's going to downpour, we will cancel).

Trail map available here: https://embed.widencdn.net/pdf/plus/scprt/z76bdshr2t/LandsfordCanalMap_Trimmed_LoRes.pdf?u=sgt8lu

This walk's (optional) theme:
Water and time

Brief:
Bring your tripod... Water over time is a classic staple of landscape photography. Consider bringing both your tripod and a Neutral Density filter, although the latter is optional as we will be losing light towards the end (sunset is at 8:20). This will aid you in being able to set longer shutter speeds to capture the motion of the river.

how_to_find_us: Cowie Weiss Theater on lower floor of the main building.
name: Hard Drive to Hard Copy
description:
Shari Zellers presents “Hard Drive to Hard Copy.” Shari, who works for Atlanta print lab MyPhotoPipe, will describe how to get your images off the computer and into print. There are five aspects she will talk about to help you get better results – Capture, Monitor Calibration, Editing, Export, and the fun part, PRINT!

Shari has worked in labs for a collective 20 years and run her own studio since 1996, currently working for the local print lab MyPhotoPipe. She has shot over 500 weddings and hundreds of corporate events that have resulted in working with millions of images in the past 30 years.
http://www.myphotopipe.com

Please join us for an insightful evening and this exciting presentation. Members as well as interested potential members are invited. For more information about Georgia Nature Photographers Association, please check out our web site
http://www.gnpa.org (http://www.gnpa.org/)

http://chattnaturecenter.org (http://chattnaturecenter.org/)

Date

Title

members who enter the club competitions.

Entering our 3 Digital and 1 Print Critique/Competitions, are great learning opportunities to improve your photography !! name: STPH - Back to Basics Part 3. Adventures in Aperture Land (Bring Camera)
description:
• What is an Aperture?
• How is it controlled?
• Why / When to think about it?

Bring your Gear (and Manual if needed). We'll answer the question above and then play around to capture images. We'll touch on the basics of exposure briefly and then explore the creative aspects of this dSLR mode.

name: Evening Photo Shoot to Lough Boora Discovery Park
description:
Hi All, we are planning an evening shoot at Lough Boora, which is near Tullamore in Co. Offaly. Reports from local photographers suggest that it is a very nice place to spend an evening out with the camera. I have set Tuesday 12th May as the date but this is weather dependent. So as with all our outings, we will check in with Met Eireann two days beforehand on Sunday 12th May and decide then for certain which might be the best evening to go, so it may be that Monday or Wednesday offer better opportunities for a nice sunset. I think that depending on traffic conditions the journey can take from 75 to 90 minutes, and some car sharing can possibly be organised. Sunset is timed for 21.16 for Dublin so it will be two or three minutes later over Co. Offaly. I suggest meeting at 07.45 but of course people will arrive when they can.
As I mentioned before all suggestions for venues for evening shoots during the Spring and Summer are very welcome.

how_to_find_us: En el portal a las 21:45 horas
name: Vamos al teatro. Magnani Aperta
group_name: La Fisgona, actividades culturales en Madrid
description:
Si no te vas de puente de San Isidro te proponemos ir a ver una obra muy especial en el domicilio de la propia actriz.

Las criticas la avalan y en La fisgona hemos conseguido una funcion especial para nosotros en exclusiva, a pesar de que todas las entradas y funciones previstas hasta Junio estaban agotadas.

En “MAGNANI APERTA” contamos la última hora de Anna Magnani en su casa antes de irse al hospital, donde murió a los pocos días.

En el centro de Madrid, con sus ruidos y sus luces, el bullicio de la gente al fondo, la actriz Arantxa de Juan ha abierto su propio domicilio para revivir allí los recuerdos de Anna Magnani, en el último día que pasó en su ático del Palacio Altieri, desde donde se dominaba toda su adorada Roma.

ENTRADAS

IMPORTANTE: Las entradas se entregarán en el portal de la C/ Desengaño nº 22 a las 21:45 horas. Se ruega máxima puntualidad ya que la función es en exclusiva para nuestro grupo de la fisgona. Desde ese momento no nos haremos responsables de la/s entradas. Tenéis nuestro teléfono en la actividad para comunicarnos por WhatsApp cualquier incidencia.

Precio: 18 €

La entrada la tendrás que abonar por transferencia bancaria una vez que realices la compra a través de:

https://lafisgona.com/producto/vamos-al-teatro-magnani-aperta/

La inscripción por Meetup es simplemente una pre-reserva.

Fecha límite para el pago de entradas: 3 de mayo de 2019.

Después de esa fecha pregúntanos por mensaje en Meetup o por WhatsApp al[masked] si tenemos disponibilidad de entradas.

SINOPSIS
Magnani Aperta se va abriendo a los recuerdos más felices y tormentosos de esta actriz auténtica y valiente, un torbellino de emociones y de personalidad poderosa. Se lo va contando a una enfermera atónita (Virginia Lázaro-Martínez), contratada por su hijo para aliviarle los dolores con morfina.

Escrita, dirigida y protagonizada por Arantxa de Juan, Magnani aperta es un canto a la vida, al amor, al coraje de una mujer que tuvo que luchar con uñas y dientes para mantenerse a flote, siempre en contacto con lo que le dictaba el corazón. La obra, toda una experiencia teatral y cinematográfica.

¡Una experiencia teatral imprescindible!

name: Tagung „LINK – Künstliche Intelligenz in Kunst und Kultur”
group_name: LINK – Künstliche Intelligenz in Kunst und Kultur
description:
***************************
Die verbindliche Anmeldung zur Tagung ist ausschließlich unter https://www.link-niedersachsen.de/tagung möglich!
***************************

KULTUR GESTALTET ZUKUNFT!

In Wirtschaft und Industrie ist Künstliche Intelligenz bereits angekommen – aber nicht in der Kultur. Für die meisten Kulturschaffenden ist dieses Thema noch absolutes Neuland. Das ändern wir! Als Landeskulturstiftung widmet sich die Stiftung Niedersachsen in ihrem Förderprogramm „LINK – Programm für künstlerische Zukunftsforschung“ in den nächsten drei Jahren der Frage, ob und wie Künstliche Intelligenz in den einzelnen Kultursparten Anwendung finden sollte. Das Experiment beginnt mit einer Tagung für Kulturschaffende. Hier schaffen wir eine gemeinsame Grundlage zu verschiedenen Themen der Künstlichen Intelligenz wie technische Voraussetzungen, Mensch-Maschine-Kommunikation, Fragen der Kreativität und des Urheberrechts von KI. Am zweiten Tag werden in Workshops mit Experten aus Wissenschaft und Kultur Ideen zur realen Anwendung entwickelt.

Begleiten Sie uns auf dieser experimentellen Forschungsreise!

ANMELDUNG
Die Anmeldung für die Tagung ist bis zum 30. April 2019 möglich unter https://www.link-niedersachsen.de/tagung

Tagungsgebühr: 75 EUR (inkl. Verpflegung)

how_to_find_us: Nos vemos en la barra del bar tomando un café
name: Pueblos de Arquitectura Negra y Cascadas del Aljibe
description:
Os proponemos otra fantástica Escapada Fotográfica a los Pueblos de Arquitectura Negra de Guadalajara. En esta ocasión visitaremos Tamajón, El Espinar, Roblelacasa, Campillo de Ranas, Robleluengo y Majaelrayo. Además haremos una pequeña ruta para visitar las Cascadas del Aljibe.

Emplazada en el Parque Natural de la Sierra Norte de Guadalajara, ubicado en el cuadrante noroccidental de la Provincia, se encuentra uno de los conjuntos más impresionantes de la arquitectura popular europea: La Arquitectura Negra de Guadalajara. Un tipo de arquitectura popular que emplea como elemento constructivo principal la pizarra, compuesto mineral de tonos grises, violetas, azulados, pardos, plateados o negruzcos.

Se trata de un grupo de pequeños y austeros pueblos que a lo largo de los tiempos han conservado su peculiar y rústica fisonomía arquitectónica. Sus sobrias construcciones se mimetizan con el entorno natural del territorio en una simbiosis casi perfecta, conformando un paisaje en perfecta armonía. La principal característica de esta arquitectura son las grandes superficies de pizarra negra que sirven tanto de cubiertas como de muros para las edificaciones, y que son extraídas del propio terreno de la zona.

Dado el clima extremadamente frío de la comarca, con largos y duros inviernos, y de frecuentes nevadas, las viviendas, con gruesos portones de madera, son de anchos muros y aposentos pequeños, con ventanas igualmente de reducido tamaño dispuestas en la fachada sur, grandes espacios reservados para cocinas y chimeneas y división del recinto con estancias bien diferenciadas para las personas, el ganado y los productos de la tierra. Además de las casas, cobertizos, iglesias, puentes, apriscos para el ganado y cercados, vienen a completar un conjunto arquitectónico de enorme belleza y singularidad.

Al finalizar la actividad tomaremos unas cañas/cafés para descansar y comentar la experiencia, antes de despedirnos 😉

Precio de la actividad, 12€ por persona. Grupo mínimo 8 / máximo 15 personas.

• Lo que hay que llevar
~ Comida y bebida. Calzado de senderismo (botas o zapatillas de trekking), una chaqueta, un corta vientos o un impermeable si procede.

• Información importante
~ Longitud de la ruta 6,4 km, desnivel +-196m
~ Nivel: Nivel Básico
~ Orientación: Fotografía-Senderismo
~ Transporte en vehículos privados.
~ Si tenéis preguntas, dudas o necesidad de alguna aclaración, por favor, no dudéis en llamar o escribir, JAIME:[masked]
~ Por favor, para evitar esperas y por respeto al resto de compañeros, si estáis apuntados y finalmente no vais a venir, debéis salir del evento o avisarme con la mayor antelación.
~ En caso de necesidad, cambio meteorológico y siempre por seguridad del grupo, la ruta podría sufrir cambios.

group_name: NANPA Nature Photography Group of Southern California
venue_name: The Huntington Library, Art Collections, and Botanical Gardens
description: The Huntington is world class in every respect. If you have never been your going to experience a real treat and outstanding photographic opportunities. There are 16 themed gardens on 120 acres of land. We will photograph flowers primarily but there will be opportunities to photograph the grounds, buildings and other objects of interest. Yes, there are birds and squirrels around too. You should check out the web site to get more insight into The Huntington. https://www.huntington.org/ The Japanese Garden/Pavilion, succulent garden and orchid garden are amazing. The place is too big to see everything in one day. You will, however, get the idea if you haven't experienced this magnificent Library and Garden. Cost: Adults $25 (19-64 yrs old); Seniors (65 ) Bathrooms available and we will eat at The Huntington. You can bring your own food or purchase food on the grounds. Note: if you want to go into some of the art buildings you are welcome to do so only no tripods, monopods or flash photography. You may want to do building/art exploring after our photography outing. Also, there is an excellent store for purchasing memorabilia. DETAILS sturdy shoes; broad brim hat; comfortable clothing it can get warm, tripod, remote, 100mm, a lens that you can use for close ups 24x70mm works; a 70x200 would work too. I will bring a 100mm, 24x70 and a 70x200mm with an extender; polarizer to get a nicer sky blue if the opportunity warrants the use of a polarizer. Extra camera is good but adds more weight to your back pack that you should bring. Bring extra memory and batteries just in case; cell phone photography is fine too.

name: ABIERTA SOLO UN DÍA AL AÑO; entramos en la Capilla que fue Cuadra de San Isidro
venue_name: Calle del Almendro, 7, Metro más cercano, La Latina
description:
HOY ES EL ÚNICO DÍA DEL AÑOS EN EL QUE SE ABRE AL PÚBLICO la que fue cuadra de San Isidro Labrador, y por tanto donde guardaba los bueyes y los animales con los que trabajaba el campo. Un lugar donde el patrón de Madrid durmió también varias noches. Hoy en ese mismo punto se encuentra La Capilla de San Isidro, donde destaca un retablo neoclásico con dos figuras que representan a San Isidro Labrador y a su mujer, Santa María de la Cabeza. En las paredes se pueden contemplar cuadros de diversos momentos de la vida de San Isidro, así como de alguno de los milagros que se le atribuyen.

Precio 6 euros; 5 se se abonan con antelación en la web: www,planbclub.es

APROVECHAREMOS LA OCASIÓN PARA CONOCER MÁS SOBRE LA HISTORIA Y MILAGROS DE SAN ISIDRO

Celebramos POR TANTO ESTE 15 DE MAYO con esta visita única. TAMBIÉN VEREMOS OTROS LUGARES RELACIONADOS CON EL PATRÓN DE MADRID como el lugar donde se encuentra su estatua más famosa y La Colegiata de San Isidro donde se encuentran los restos del SAnto y de su esposa, Santa María de la Cabeza

El Ayuntamiento de Madrid, agradecido por los servicios de los negocios centenarios a la ciudad, encargó al mismísimo MINGOTE crear unos dibujos en unas placas de bronce.
En el recorrido hoy, visitaremos también algunos de estos negocios centenarios, todos ellos en el centro de Madrid, y conoceremos su historia. Por ejemplo veremos el primer restaurante del mundo, el primer hotel de España, un restaurante de 1880 con salones de estilo imperial y Romanticismo patente, una taberna de 1857 decorada con azulejos, espejos y cuadros castizos, especializada en cocido madrileño, una coqueta tienda de bombones creada en 1915, o una farmacia con el encanto y los típicos botes de medicamentos utilizados hace más de cien años.
El mismísimo Michael Jackson ha sido uno de los célebres clientes de una tienda de capas centenaria de Madrid.
¿Sabes dónde se encuentra este comercio en cuyo escaparate se puede ver al famoso cantante vistiendo una de sus prendas?

name: Urban Athletics: Kickball for Grownups (Co-ed)
group_name: I wanted to do that...Just not alone!!
venue_address_1: Corner of Houston Street and Avenue of the Americas (6th Avenue)
description:
It's time to get kicking. Kick your neighbor. Kick your brother. Kick the big red ball. Just don't kick your dog. Game. On.

If you don't know, now you know...

If you've never played the game of kickball as a kid you must have grown up on Mars. But as a quick primer, it's a game with rules similar to baseball -- except instead of using a bat to hit a little ball, you use your feet to kick a ball about 10x the size of a baseball. Kick the ball, run to the base, avoid getting your ball caught mid-air or yourself tagged out. Easy. And no athletic skill is necessary, just the ability to kick! Go out and practice now to get ready. Kick the postman when he delivers your bills. Kick that neighbor who won't turn down his stereo. Just get kicking!

If you haven't played the game in 20 years, here are the general rules we will be using https://dl.dropboxusercontent.com/u/64476072/Kickball%20Rules.pdf

A $3.00 organization fee will be collected at this event, your host is in the running for hardest working person on meetup.

The important stuff...

• This is a co-ed game so ladies don't be shy to sign up. And it doesn't matter if you have no athletic ability, you just have to be willing to have a little fun.

• Dress for physical activity! You'll be kicking and running so wear your sneaks, shorts and a t-shirt.

• Rain or similar un-favorable weather cancels the meetup. Not!

• Check the meetup site before leaving for last minute updates as well as my mobile phone number.

• Please DO NOT RSVP if you do not seriously plan to attend as space is limited. No flakes allowed! If you RSVP and I notice that you have a number of no shows or have a history of last minute cancellations, you will be removed.

name: Write to Publish, Publish to Sell
description:
Do you want to write to publish a book, but are confused by all the advice out there about the right path to seeing your book in print? Do you want to know about how to sell your book once it is published as well as how people get it on a major best sellers list?

Should you find an agent? (And how do you do that?) Should you go to publishers directly? Should you self-publish? Should you go print-on-demand? Yoinks! It seems like publishing is the new wild west.

While publishing is easier than it's ever been, it's also more confusing. The former gatekeepers no longer hold all the keys, but there are also a lot of people out there selling counterfeit ones. How do you figure out what the best way to do it is when all you really want to do is sit down and write?

BWA has a handful of people who know the ropes, from published authors to those of us who work in the seedy underbelly of the industry. Wanna know what we've done and what's worked?

Then this is the meeting for you.

(Note, parking is free for the first 1.5 hours and after 7:00 pm. So if you show up after 5:30, all you have to do is put in your license plate number and you are good until we're done. 😁 )

name: Monthly themes and critique - Flash Workshop
description:
Monthly Topic:

David Boyd will briefly review what he covered in his flash presentation in October. We will then have hands on time to demonstrate and to work with various types of flash accessories and settings.

You may have heard that flash is too hard to use, too complicated, and that it makes photos look washed out and artificial. In this meetup, we're going to look at how and when to use a flash, demonstrate that settings are a lot simpler than they seem and prove that a flash can enhance a photograph, while making it look like natural light. We will look at when a flash can improve a photograph and when a flash should not be used. Most of the meetup will be hands on and we will look at diffusers, reflectors, better beamers, and other, inexpensive devices. Bring your camera and flash. If you don’t have one, we will have some to share.

See you there...

The leadership team.

how_to_find_us: We will be in Suite 206.
name: CritCon - Critique for Confidence
group_name: The Denver See Like a Photographer Group
description:
CritCon - Critique for Confidence

I, like many of you, sit in a dark room in front of computer screen and edit. That little voice inside your head constantly asking...is this working...does this look good...is it compelling...is it my best work?

Having come from a job where I had 15 other photographers to turn around and ask those questions to and get immediate feedback...I yearn for that critique, the honesty of a comrade in developer and fixer (or for the new age- a comrade in pixels) to help me improve my craft and forge my vision into a force of self expression and engagement.

This will be a night to be courageous and put your images out there for peers to view, love, praise, and polish.

Each image maker will bring 1 photo (or email it to Erik at [masked]). Make sure the image is at least 1420px on the longest size. Let me know if you need help with your image sizing especially if you are presenting an iPhone image.

Some Tips on How to Critique:

Stop, Look, Understand, Critique - This is to start a dialogue not be mean or to show how much you know about photography. People are coming here to improve. Be fair, kind and direct.

A Critique Is Not an Opinion

Art is full of subjective quantities. It's also full of objective quantities. Focus on the latter. There's nothing wrong with expressing a personal preference, so long as it's framed as a preference and not a critique. Critiques should focus on factually based characteristics. If someone chose to color tone a photograph a certain way, you can certainly express your preference for another color palette, but you can't argue the superiority of one or another. If someone presents a blurry shot, there are objective, measurable quantities such as shutter speed, aperture, and ISO that can be invoked to discuss why the shot was blurry and how it can be remedied.

Also, come to the critique with an open mind. Every one has an objective opinion about art, but if 3 or more people have the same opinion it might need be taken into consideration...Too Positive or Too Negative..ignore it. Most important to consider...are you ready to have this image critiqued...

If you cannot critique someones work, how can you be ready to have yours critiqued. Have courage to critique and confidence to build on your critiques.

This group will of course morph and grow. Suggestions are wanted and loved.

Erik Holladay-McCann will be our moderator. He will help guide and encourage the critique. We will not allow personal attacks on the image makers themselves. This is a space for caring for our fellow image makers, expanding our perfection of the craft, and most of all building a community that lifts us all to the next level in our photography. A rising tide carries all ships....

Join Nature Therapy Guide, Kaitlin Powers, to learn about how time spent in nature helps you rejuvenate and be more resilient in your day-to-day life. She will share scientific findings on the benefits of spending time outdoors, examine what practices help us better reap these rewards, and offer some tips on how to fit wellness through nature into your daily life.

Kaitlin Powers is the Director and Lead Instructor for Humans in Nature Wellness Services, a small business that promotes health and wellness through nature connection and outdoor experiences. Since 2015, Kaitlin has partnered with municipalities, community groups, and conservation-minded organizations to lead hundreds of community members in nature-based wellness programs each year.

description:
Ausstellung | Lesung | Film | Konzert

Ein Abend rund um den Einsatz neuer Technologien in Kunst und Kultur
im Künstlerhaus Hannover.

Veranstalter: Kunstverein Hannover, Literaturhaus Hannover und Kommunales Kino Hannover gemeinsam mit der Stiftung Niedersachsen

PROGRAMM

19:00 Uhr
Kuratorenführung: „Artistic Intelligence“ mit Sergey Harutoonian
Kunstverein Hannover
Die Ausstellung versammelt Werke u. a. von Harun Farocki, Mario Klingemann, Helen Knowles und Anna Ridler. Der Kunstverein ist bis 23 Uhr geöffnet.

19:30 Uhr
Lesung: Timo Daum „Die Künstliche Intelligenz des Kapitals“ (Edition Nautilus)
Literaturhaus Hannover
Timo Daum beleuchtet technische, ökonomische, politische und soziale Aspekte der Zukunftstechnologie | Moderation: Ulrich Kühn.

20:15 Uhr
Film: Ex Machina
Kino im Künstlerhaus
Science-Fiction? Eine erschreckend greifbare Utopie über Künstliche Intelligenz und die Frage, was Menschlichkeit wirklich heißt. Regie: Alex Garland | FSK 12 | 104 Min (USA/GB 2014).

21:30 Uhr
Konzert: Phillip Schulze
Kunstverein Hannover | Phillip Schulze (* 1979 in Düsseldorf) ist Komponist und Computer Performer. In seinem Konzert erzeugt er mehrdimensionale Klangmutationen, die elektronisch in Echtzeit generiert werden.

EINTRITT
Lesung inkl. Ausstellung: 12/6 €
Film inkl. Ausstellung: 6,50/4,50 €
Ausstellung: 6/4 €

Inhaber der NDR Kultur Karte erhalten ermäßigten Eintritt.

Die Veranstaltung ist Teil der Tagung „LINK – Künstliche Intelligenz in Kunst und Kultur” der Stiftung Niedersachsen. Für Tagungsteilnehmer ist der Eintritt frei.

name: Cultures in Transition by Oliver Klink
group_name: Palo Alto Camera Club Photography Meetup
description:
Cultures in Transition explores the changes that people go through, the subtleties that make their life evolve, their spiritual guiding light. Over 15 years, in five Asian countries (Bhutan, China, India, Mongolia, Myanmar), Oliver Klink photographed environmental portraits of the continuity between family, work, and spirituality. There was no separation, but peoples’ concerns about how ‘progress’ can create disconnection and alienation between themselves and their communities became more evident. This fluidity of life is at the core of Cultures in Transition.

Oliver Klink will discuss the stories behind the project, the rewards/challenges of working on a long-term project, and what turned this into an award-winning book and traveling exhibit. Signed books will be available for purchase. www.culturesintransition.com

Register at https://www.eventbrite.com/e/cultures-in-transition-by-oliver-klink-registration-60563593338

name: Artistic Photography Today-Artists Re-Presenting Reality with John Mariana
description:
Doors will open at 6:30 pm. 6:30 to 7:00 pm will be time for socializing. Presentation will begin at 7:15 pm.

Photographic Artists make Photographic Art, not take them, shoot them, capture them or snap them. They see the world differently and then show others how they see and feel the world. The final artistic print is their representation of the world through their eyes, mind, heart and creative artistic talents. The tools of the craft are a camera and a lens but the print is result of their artistic vision.

Ansel Adams wrote in one of his books that the image taken in the field, although very reliant on proper technique, was merely the canvas from which to work his darkroom artistic magic.

Digital images are imported to Photoshop or other editing software. Optimization takes place including the digital blending of different versions of an image and completely separate images.

Photographic software was introduced 20 years ago. Today photographic artists create new and intriguing works of art and most galleries and museums have come to respect and exhibit digital art. Photographers creating artful prints have always used the tools available to them to “create” their vision of a scene, a subject or an entirely new re-presentation of reality.

John will present Three Stages of photographic skill development with examples for each stage and a demonstration of layers for composites to demonstrate how a person gets from the photo to Artistic Photography.

Stage 1 - Skills Development - In Camera and Simple Enhancements
Stage 2 - Artistic Photography
Stage 3 - Digital

About John—
In 1980 John started using photography in connection to his art background to create color images. By 1984 black and white prints became his specialty. Today, John uses photography to create fine art black and white and color prints expressing his thoughts and artistic vision. Until 1990, 35mm was his preferred film format. Today John uses medium format, large format negatives and digital files to bring a new and different look to his work. A uniqueness of composition, contrasts, colors and tones comes from formal art training at age 11. Formal art courses continued through his undergraduate studies. Although photography was not the first medium used as an expression of creativity, the early artistic training combined with photography gives his images a unique visual and emotional presentation. Studies with such noted photographers as Howard Bond, John Sexton and Dan Anderson provided training in the style of photography taught by Ansel Adams in the Owens Valley Workshops. John''s current works include color prints, black and white prints, warm brown sepia toned prints and hand tinted prints. John was President of the Chicago Area Camera Clubs Association in 1990. This organization consisted of 40 clubs in the greater Chicago metropolitan area. He became the Chairman of the Chicago Area Photographic School from 1986 to 1990. Co-founded the not-for-profit American Photographic Academy dedicated to Education In The Art Of Photography and provided two day workshops with John Sexton, Jerry Ulesman and others.

We look forward to seeing you on May 15th.

name: Shooting with The Sun with Jon Lorentz
description:
PLEASE REGISTER: -->> https://events-canonusa.ddreg.me/Events/40604/shooting-with-the-sun-with-jon-lorentz

Speedlites! Strobes! LED Panels! Reflectors!
It’s easy to get caught up in the plethora of lighting options available to a photographer in this day and age, but one source remains true—the sun. Imagine, if you will, while you’re en route to an amazing location, your batteries die, or your reflector tears, or, you could’ve forgotten that ONE cord you needed—things happen. So let’s take a step back and look at how to plan for the worst but still achieve the best.
Join Jon Lorentz as we discuss shooting with the sun—and only the sun.

name: May 2019 Challenge and Critique
description:
ALL OF THE IMPORTANT SUBMISSION DETAILS ARE LISTED HERE. PLEASE READ THEM:
http://posneg.com/critiques/

YOU MUST BE A MEMBER TO ATTEND!!

For this month I am going to challenge you to a technique that I don't think I have challenged you to in the 8 years I have been doing these assignments.

MAY'S THEME: SLOW SHUTTER SPEED

Your specific challenge for May is to create up to three AMAZING photographs that you have created by using a shutter speed of
ONE SECOND OR LONGER.

Could it be a waterfall, a pinwheel in the wind, the blurred motion of a train? Maybe it's a night sky, a night scene, or an architectural interior? It's your call, BUT BE DIFFERENT!

***EVERYONE NEEDS TO READ THIS CAREFULLY***

Put your creative brain to work and start photographing anything that fits the theme. THIS SHOULD BE FUN AND QUITE ENJOYABLE!

PLEASE READ THE LINK BELOW TO THE SUBMISSION DETAILS CAREFULLY AND COMPLETELY
http://posneg.com/critiques/

This is our fifth monthly CHALLENGE & CRITIQUE session for 2019 in which you may submit up to three photographs for a professional critique and win CASH PRIZES.

The Green Turtle is generous enough to provide a private room with tables, chairs, and servers to our group. I ask that you order dinner, drinks, or appetizers during our meeting please.

The main purpose of the CHALLENGE & CRITIQUE session is to help you learn and grow as a photographer and to learn how to start thinking outside the box, and to stimulate you to shoot NEW material. You can only submit images if you will be in attendance for the critique session.

All attendees will be required to make a $6 cash donation upon arrival into the meeting, whether you entered images or not. $1 of your donation will go to continuing educational materials for the runners up.

PLEASE BRING EXACT CASH.

After every critique session, a FIRST, SECOND, and THIRD place image will be chosen. FIRST place will receive 50% of the total money collected (less everyone's dollar), SECOND place will receive 30%, and THIRD place will receive 20%. Winning images will be chosen based on composition, clarity, visual impact, inspiration, and how well it fits the challenge theme.

Be creative and submit up to three images.

Have fun and SHOOT SOMETHING NEW!

**Your images must have been taken after March 20th, 2019**
**Final deadline to submit images will be midnight on May 13th, 2019

name: C-41 Film Development
description:
C-41 is the development process for color negative film. This class will be a simple demonstration of the C-41 process and how you can do it at home or at the TPS darkroom. Color negative film is very forgiving and I find the development process to be easier than traditional BW or E-6.

No prior film experience is needed. If you have any color negative film that needs development, feel free to bring it along.

name: Mid week Crazy stairs Climbing !
description:
Join us in our Facebook Group ~ WLC Travels & Adventures (https://www.facebook.com/groups/WLC.Travels.Adventures/)

Let's meet at the lift lobby from 6.45pm (for those early birds), we will start off once briefing is done. We will start climbing from Blk 79A clockwise up and take the elevator down and repeat with an anti clockwise stairs. Those who are coming late, do look out for us. Give us a text when you reach. Please do not come later than 800pm as we aim to finish by 830pm latest.

Our usual schedule

645pm to 700pm - meet, brief, stretch and warm up

700pm to 830pm - do at your own pace to conquer as many towers as you can.

830pm to 900pm - dinner and catch up nearby coffeeshop

Event Hosts

Ten -[masked]

Magdalene -[masked]

Kelvin -[masked]

Note : This is just an invitation from fellow meet up friends to exercise together, don't feel stressed over any disclaimers. just come and join us to lose some calories and don't think too much. At the end of the day it is about being healthy and knowing each other better in the process. :)

P/S: There is no locker or facilities to deposit our bags. Hence do bring a bagpack that you can carry along when climbing the stairs.

Did you know?

If you’re looking to burn calories, lose weight and strengthen and tone major muscle groups, stair climbing provides astounding results. It is widely regarded as one of the most efficient and effective cardio and strength building workouts today.

Cardio/Calorie Benefits

Burn more calories climbing stairs. It engages the body’s largest muscle groups to repeatedly lift your body weight up, step after step. Using your largest muscles to carry your own weight uphill is far superior to exercising on a flat treadmill when it comes to work performed and calories burned.

Strength and Muscle Toning Benefits

The simple act of maintaining balance engages core muscles with every step, building strength and endurance . Tone and sculpt your entire lower body. Stair climbing engages every major muscle in your lower body as many as 120+ times/minute: glutes, hamstrings, quadriceps and calves. High repetitions are famous for building lean muscle and burning fat which results in toned and sculpted muscles. You can achieve high work efforts while moving at very low speeds relative to other workout options, minimizing the toll/stress on the body.
